[Event "A Deep Dive into the Caro-Kann: Advance Variation for Black"]
[Site "Introduction"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ Welcome to my course Caro-Kann Advance 1... e4 3.e5 Bf5! for Black. It is a standalone course that provides Black with a full repertoire against the modern mainline 3.e5 in the Caro-Kann. Of course, White can try many different strategies against the solid and firm Caro-Kann, but 3.e5 is clearly the most dangerous - and it is also the most popular at all levels. } 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 { Black has two options: } 3... Bf5 $1 { This is the real Caro-Kann move. After all, the opening is designed to get this light-squared bishop out. The alternative This course closes the gap and gives Black new possibilities. The position after } ( 3... c5 { and } ) ( 3... Bf5 { . } ) ( 3... c5 { is definitely playable. It leads to very complex and dynamic positions that can be hard to navigate with Black. White gets a serious initiative after either } 4. dxc5 { or } ( 4. Nf3 { , but Black surely gets good counterchances. Theoretically, it holds water so far, but the sharp positions demanding very exact reactions and good defensive skills from Black are not to everybody's liking. [--] Most Caro-Kann players like to have control! That's why you should switch to 3...Bf5! In my own course LTR: Schandorff's Caro-Kann, I also gave 3...c5, as many other authors have done recently. I mainly did this for three reasons: 1\. I wanted to challenge myself and deliver some new stuff to make the course different from my books. 2\. I am an opening aficionado and love analyzing interesting lines, and 3...c5 leads to some fascinating positions. 3\. It gives Black good winning chances. All the above are really good arguments, especially if you are armed with an engine, but they are not necessarily suitable for the practical player who will actually get the positions on the board. Furthermore, I gave 3...Bf5! in my two books, Grandmaster Repertoire and Playing the Caro-Kann, and I have played it almost exclusively in my own games. I believe it is the correct positional move. } ) ) ( 3... Bf5 { is very strategically interesting. White's pawn on e5 secures a lot of extra space and it makes it hard for Black to develop the kingside. [--] On the other hand, Black's centre is firm and the light-squared bishop got out, which is a big positional achievement. Black will play ...e6 next and then start attacking the white centre with ...c5. Because the position is so closed, Black is in no hurry to get castled. The king is safe on e8 for the time being. White has easy development and good squares for the pieces, so it is tempting to play active and strive for the initiative. [--] For Black, it is extremely important to consolidate, but at the same time always look for counterplay. The black pawn structure is very resilient, and if White pushes too hard their attack might backfire. [--] All in all, there are more than enough to think about for both sides to ensure a complex battle. } ) 4. Nf3 { • • • • • • Apart from the already mentioned tries, White has a bunch of more rare lines like } ( 4. Nf3 { is by far most played move and probably also the best. White just develops without compromising the structure. Next up is Be2 and O-O, the so-called Short Variation. Only after that, depending on Black's setup, will White decide on a specific plan. [--] This is a both simple and deep way of playing. White can play positionally and try to secure the centre with c3, or blow everything open with the dynamic break c4. The Short Variation is, in my opinion, the hardest line to face in the entire Caro-Kann. So I will provide you with two good ways to fight it: a solid setup and a more complicated one. Then you will be well armed. } ) ( 4. h4 { is the second most played move. Especially the popular Tal Variation after } 4... h5 5. Bd3 { has given Black players some headache. Also here, I will supply detailed analysis and a good solution. [--] But White has many other tries, ranging from the over-aggressive to the more modest. } ) ( 4. g4 { and } ) ( 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 { belong in the first category. It is playable for White, but the move g4 seriously compromises White's own structure and leaves a lot of holes in the position. Play becomes sharp, but Black can withstand the assault. } ) ( 4. c4 { or with } ) ( 4. h4 h5 { included is another direct attempt to attack Black's position from the get go. Also here, the structure is somewhat compromised. It Black takes on c4 there will be a nice square on d5 for a knight. } ) ( 4. Nd2 e6 5. Nb3 { Trying to stop Black liberating move c6-c5 is another popular way for White to play in the more modest category. } ) ( 4. Bd3 { , } ) ( 4. Ne2 { , } ) ( 4. Be3 { , } ) ( 4. c3 { and some others. They are all in this course. Everything is covered. [--] So, let's jump right into it! } ) * 

[Event "A Deep Dive into the Caro-Kann: Advance Variation for Black"]
[Site "4.Bd3"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.Bd3"]
[Black "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 $1 { The bishop gets out. Later White's centre can be attacked with ...c5 or ...f6. } 4. Bd3 { [%cal Gd3f5] This is quite popular, especially at the club level. It is a simple move - probably too simple. Positionally speaking we don't mind exchanging light- squared bishops, hoping that White's remaing one on c1 will be rather bad in the long term. } 4... Bxd3 5. Qxd3 e6 { [%cal Gc6c5] } 6. Nf3 { A natural developing move. } ( 6. c3 { strengthens the pawn chain prophylactically, expecting ...c5. Black replies } 6... c5 { and after } 7. Ne2 { or } ( 7. Nf3 { play transposes to either **6.Ne2** or **6.Nf3**. } ) ) 6... c5 { [%csl Rd4] The usual strike. If you love endings, you can try The flexible } ( 6... Qa5+ { followed by ...Qa6. } ) ( 6... Nd7 7. O-O Ne7 { is probably ok too, but I prefer something more active. } ) 7. c3 Nd7 $1 { [%cal Gg8e7] [%cal Ge7c6] Most people go for } ( 7... Nc6 { , but this is clever: the g8-knight is heading for c6 with a very harmonious position. } ) * 

[Event "A Deep Dive into the Caro-Kann: Advance Variation for Black"]
[Site "Tal Variation: 4.h4 h5 5.c4"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Tal Variation: 4.h4 h5 5.c4"]
[Black "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 $1 { The bishop gets out. Later White's centre can be attacked with ...c5 or ...f6. } 4. h4 h5 $1 { Preventing **g4**. Don't fall for } ( 4... e6 $2 5. g4 Be4 6. f3 Bg6 7. h5 { . } ) 5. c4 { This is also quite a popular move. } ( 5. c4 { looks aggressive, but it is also a good positional move: White will play Nc3 next and hopes to enjoy active pieces and a lot of extra space. } ) 5... e6 6. Nc3 dxc4 $1 { [%csl Gd5] An important strategic decision. Black changes the structure to get a nice square on d5. } 7. Bxc4 Nd7 { [%cal Gd7b6] [%cal Gg8h6] [%cal Gf8e7] [%csl Rh4] [%csl Gd5] Black has a lot of possibilities in this interesting position with chances for both sides. Probably we will play ...Be7 to attack h4 and force White to weaken the kingside with g2-g3. The knight can go to h6. We are not afraid of Bxh6 as we can just take back with the rook. Later ...Nb6 will come. There is a nice square on d5 and often we will castle long. You can check the theory section (See "theory section" variation from the PGN) for more details. } * 

