1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 $1 { The bishop gets out. Later White's centre can be attacked with ...c5 or ...f6. } 4. h4 h5 $1 { Preventing **g4**. Don't fall for } ( 4... e6 $2 5. g4 Be4 6. f3 Bg6 7. h5 { . } ) 5. Bd3 { [%cal Gd3f5] A simple and easy to understand move: White exchanges Black's strong Caro-Kann bishop. } 5... Bxd3 6. Qxd3 { This is a better version of the bishop exchange for White. Here they get the g5-square. } 6... Qa5+ $1 { [%cal Rb1d2] [%cal Rc1d2] An important move. } ( 6... e6 { is also possible, but then } 7. Bg5 { is annoying. } ) 7. b4 $5 { A surprising pawn sacrifice. } 7... Qa6 $5 { [%cal Ga6d3] [%cal Gb8a6] I suggest this as a simple solution. You can also take the pawn: } ( 7... Qxb4+ 8. Nd2 e6 9. Rb1 Qe7 { when Black is solid, but White has some long-term pressure as compensation. In the theory section (See "theory section" variation from the PGN) I explore this line in much more detail. } ) 8. e6 $5 { The most dangerous. } 8... Qxd3 9. cxd3 { The intermediate check White has scored well from the position after } ( 9. exf7+ Kxf7 { only helps Black to develop. } ) ( 9. cxd3 { , but Black is absolutely ok. } ) 9... fxe6 { [%csl Ge5] [%csl Gf4] [%csl Gg5] White has excellent compensation with good squares on e5, f4 and g5. However, by returning the extra pawn at the right moment Black gets fine play. } 10. Nd2 Nh6 { [%cal Gh6f5] } 11. Ndf3 Nf5 12. Nh3 { [%csl Ge5] [%csl Gf4] [%csl Gg5] White controls e5, f4 and g5, so it looks quite dangerous. An appropiate return of the pawn solves all development issues for Black. } 12... g6 13. Nf4 a5 $1 { [%csl Rb4] [%cal Ga8a2] With good counterplay. Possible continuations are } 14. Nxg6 ( 14. Nxe6 Kd7 { , which you can see in a nice game (See "nice game" variation from the PGN) in the Model Games section. } ) 14... Rg8 { and } * 

