1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 $1 { The bishop gets out. Later White's centre can be attacked with ...c5 or ...f6. } 4. h4 h5 $1 { Preventing **g4**. Don't fall for } ( 4... e6 $2 5. g4 Be4 6. f3 Bg6 7. h5 { . } ) 5. Bd3 Bxd3 6. Qxd3 { This is a better version of the bishop exchange for White. Here they get the g5-square. } 6... Qa5+ $1 { An important move. } ( 6... e6 { is also possible, but then } 7. Bg5 { is annoying. } ) 7. Nd2 { [%cal Ya5a6] [%cal Yc2c4] This is clearly the most played move and one of the most important modern Caro-Kann lines. } 7... e6 8. Nf3 Nh6 { [%cal Gh6f5] [%csl Gf5] The modern response. The knight is heading for the excellent f5-square. } 9. O-O Nf5 { A very important position arises. Here White has tried different ideas. Play can continue } 10. Nb3 Qa6 11. Qd1 b6 { followed by ...c5 with good counterplay. You can see much more in the theory section (See "theory section" variation from the PGN), and there is also a nice Model Game (See "Model Game" variation from the PGN). } * 

