1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 $1 { The bishop gets out. Later White's centre can be attacked with ...c5 or ...f6. } 4. c4 { This line should be compared with the line } ( 4. h4 h5 5. c4 { . Basically, White strategy is the same: to develop very actively. } ) 4... e6 { [%cal Gf8b4] [%cal Gg8e7] [%cal Gd5c4] Because nothing has happened on the kingside yet, Black doesn't need to look out for any Bg5-stuff and has some interesting extra options. } 5. Nc3 Bb4 $5 { This is one of Black's extra possibilities. Often Black plays } ( 5... Ne7 { or even } ) ( 5... dxc4 { , but I like this } ) ( 5... Bb4 { plan very much. It leads to an interesting positional struggle where Black is doing great. } ) 6. Qb3 { [%csl Rb4] The most played move, attacking Black's bishop and hoping for some clarity. } 6... a5 { [%csl Gb4] A cool idea, protecting the bishop. } 7. a3 dxc4 $1 { [%csl Rb3] A good intermediate move, getting the d5-square. } 8. Bxc4 Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3 Nd7 { [%csl Gd5] [%cal Gd7b6] [%cal Gg8e7] Black is fine. The knight can go to b6 and d5 and the other knight will be developed to e7 with a harmonious position. } * 

[Event "A Deep Dive into the Caro-Kann: Advance Variation for Black"]
[Site "4.Nd2 with 6.Be3"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.Nd2 with 6.Be3"]
[Black "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 $1 { The bishop gets out. Later White's centre can be attacked with ...c5 or ...f6. } 4. Nd2 { Quite a popular move for people who want a deep strategic game without having to learn a lot of theory. } 4... e6 5. Nb3 { [%cal Gb3c5] [%csl Gc5] This is the point of **4.Nd2** : White will make it hard for us to push ...c5. We will manage to get this break in somehow, even if it costs us the pair of bishops. } 5... Nd7 { [%cal Gc6c5] Fighting for ...c5. } 6. Be3 { Still fighting for the c5-square. } 6... a5 $1 { [%cal Ga5a4] Black has played many things here. I like to throw in ...a5-a4. } 7. a4 f6 { [%csl Re5] The thematic attack on White's centre begins. If we can't get ...c5 in, then ...f6 is a natural way to get counterplay, with similar play as in the Short Variation. } * 

[Event "A Deep Dive into the Caro-Kann: Advance Variation for Black"]
[Site "4.Nd2 with 6.Nf3"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.Nd2 with 6.Nf3"]
[Black "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 $1 { The bishop gets out. Later White's centre can be attacked with ...c5 or ...f6. } 4. Nd2 { Quite a popular move for people who want a deep strategic game without having to learn a lot of theory. } 4... e6 5. Nb3 { [%cal Gb3c5] [%csl Gc5] This is the point of **4.Nd2** : White will make it hard for us to push ...c5. We will manage to get this break in somehow, even if it costs us the pair of bishops. } 5... Nd7 { [%cal Gc6c5] Fighting for ...c5. } 6. Nf3 { White concentrates on development. } 6... a6 $5 { [%cal Gc6c5] [%csl Gb5] Other moves are possible, of course, but I think it is worth the time to cover the b5-square. When we push ...c5, the position might open up and Bb5+ can be disturbing. } 7. Be2 c5 8. dxc5 { If White doesn't take we can consider pushing ...c4. } 8... Bxc5 { [%cal Gg8e7] Capturing with the bishop is best. After } ( 8... Nxc5 9. O-O { it is difficult for Black to develop the kingside. Quick development is more important than the bishops! } ) 9. Nxc5 Nxc5 { [%cal Gg8e7] [%cal Ge8g8] So White got the bishop pair. Yes, but Black is ready to finish development with ...Ne7 and ...O-O. } 10. Nd4 Ne7 { [%cal Ge7f5] [%cal Ge8g8] [%csl Gf5] White is even allowed to take on f5 as well. We are ready to castle and must be fine. } 11. O-O O-O 12. Nxf5 Nxf5 { [%cal Ga8c8] [%cal Gd8c7] [%cal Gf8d8] The knights are not worse than the bishops. An interesting game is ahead. } * 

[Event "A Deep Dive into the Caro-Kann: Advance Variation for Black"]
[Site "4.c3"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.c3"]
[Black "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 $1 { The bishop gets out. Later White's centre can be attacked with ...c5 or ...f6. } 4. c3 { [%csl Gc3] [%csl Gd4] [%csl Ge5] Another solid line. White creates a strong pawn chain. This means that our standard break ...c5 loses some of its sting, but instead White's centre can be attacked from the front with ...f6. } 4... e6 5. Be3 { A logical follow-up. } 5... Qb6 { [%csl Rb2] Hitting b2. } 6. Qb3 { A typical position with queens opposite each other. Neither player wants to be the one to take first and open the a-file for the opponent. } 6... Nd7 7. Nd2 f6 $1 { [%csl Re5] Going for immediate counterplay. This time we attack White's centre from the front. } 8. f4 { Trying to keep the strong centre together. } 8... g5 $1 { [%csl Re5] [%csl Rf4] But we won't allow it! This move gives Black excellent play. A major point is the following natural continuation. } 9. exf6 g4 $1 { [%csl Rf3] A strong positional move that takes the f3-square away from White's knights. Next Black will restore material equality by taking the f-pawn with a good game. White has other moves than **9.exf6** , but Black has no problems and is already fighting for the initiative as you can see in the theory section (See "theory section" variation from the PGN). } * 

[Event "A Deep Dive into the Caro-Kann: Advance Variation for Black"]
[Site "4.Nc3 Shirov: 7.h4 with 9.Nxh5 #1"]
