1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 $1 { The bishop gets out. Later White's centre can be attacked with ...c5 or ...f6. } 4. Nc3 { Positionally speaking, the knight is misplaced here, blocking the c-pawn. There is cunning idea behind } ( 4. Nc3 { , though. } ) 4... e6 5. g4 { The Shirov variation. White goes all-in on sharp play, trying to get the initiative with very aggressive moves. Black's structure is very firm and not so easy to overrun and modern engines confirm that this is a risky strategy for White. } 5... Bg6 6. Nge2 { [%cal Gh2h4] [%cal Ge2f4] [%csl Rg6] White wants to continue with **h4**. It is necessary to prepare this with } ( 6. Nge2 { , as the premature } ) ( 6. h4 { is met with } 6... h5 $1 { , when closing the kingside with } 7. g5 { gives Black a free hand on the other side: } 7... c5 { and Black already has good play. } ) 6... c5 $1 { Black strives for active counterplay. } 7. h4 h5 $1 { A pawn sacrifice that slows White's play down. Black's play is in general based on very direct counterplay. Some of the hardcore lines are quite complicated, but the basic logic is simple: We create our own chances by fighting fire with fire! } 8. Nf4 Bh7 $1 { Sacrificing the h-pawn. } 9. Nxh5 cxd4 $1 { [%cal Gb8c6] It is important to destroy White's centre. Black gets promising play in all lines. Play typically can go in two directions. } 10. Nb5 { The main move. } 10... Nc6 11. Nxd4 Nge7 { Black has good play for the pawn. You can find a lot more analysis in the theory section (See "theory section" variation from the PGN). Here I will just show how the line can continue: } 12. Bb5 { Pinning the knight. } 12... Qc7 13. f4 { Protecting the e5-pawn. } 13... O-O-O { Black is ready to take on d4 with good play. } * 

