1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 $1 { The bishop gets out. Later White's centre can be attacked with ...c5 or ...f6. } 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 { The Short variation. This is the best set-up for White in my opinion, and it is also for a good reason the most popular line in the entire Caro-Kann **3.e5 Bf5** system. White continues to develop before any major decisions are made. Next they can castle short. Black in the meantime must show their chosen set- up and White can respond accordingly. [--] At heart, the Short variation is a positional way of playing for White with quick development and extra space, but White can also strike with c4 and try to fight for the initiative. Because of the enormous popularity of this variation at all levels, I have decided to give two good ways to meet it. One is the principal counterstrike in the centre with } 5... a5 $5 { [%cal Ga5a4] This surprising move in AlphaZero style has been played several times by Magnus Carlsen and many other top players have used it. The idea is to grab more space on the queenside with ...a4, which Black can afford because the centre is closed and White has no immediate targets. } ( 5... c5 { . This is a big theoretical line, but as far as I can see Black keeps the balance everywhere. It is a very concrete and solid line. [--] My other suggestion is the fresh idea } ) ( 5... a5 $1 $2 { , and this is the move I will concentrate on here in the Quickstarter. But, of course, you can find deep coverage of } ) ( 5... c5 { in the theory section as well, starting here (See "here" variation from the PGN). } ) 6. O-O { White ignores Black's plan and just continues with natural moves. } 6... a4 { White has tried a bunch of different moves here. } 7. c4 { White fights for the initiative. } 7... dxc4 8. Bxc4 Nd7 { Here Carlsen and others have played the natural } ( 8... Nd7 { intending Nb6. I give this as the mainline, but in the theory section (See "theory section" variation from the PGN) you can see that I also suggest the novelty } ) ( 8... Ne7 { , as there is a nice square on d5. Black is doing really well in these lines. } ) * 

