1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 $1 { The bishop gets out. Later White's centre can be attacked with ...c5 or ...f6. } 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 { The Short variation. This is the best set-up for White in my opinion, and it is also for a good reason the most popular line in the entire Caro-Kann **3.e5 Bf5** system. White continues to develop before any major decisions are made. Next they can castle short. Black in the meantime must show their chosen set- up and White can respond accordingly. [--] At heart, the Short variation is a positional way of playing for White with quick development and extra space, but White can also strike with c4 and try to fight for the initiative. Because of the enormous popularity of this variation at all levels, I have decided to give two good ways to meet it. One is the principal counterstrike in the centre with } 5... a5 $5 { This surprising move in AlphaZero style has been played several times by Magnus Carlsen and many other top players have used it. The idea is to grab more space on the queenside with ...a4, which Black can afford because the centre is closed and White has no immediate targets. } ( 5... c5 { . This is a big theoretical line, but as far as I can see Black keeps the balance everywhere. It is a very concrete and solid line. [--] My other suggestion is the fresh idea } ) ( 5... a5 $1 $2 { , and this is the move I will concentrate on here in the Quickstarter. But, of course, you can find deep coverage of } ) ( 5... c5 { in the theory section as well, starting here (See "here" variation from the PGN). } ) 6. a4 { The automatic reaction, just stopping all of Black's ideas to expand on the queenside. } 6... f6 { [%csl Re5] Black refrains from the ...**c5** -plan and instead challenges White's centre from the front. It is also possible to start with } ( 6... Nd7 { and then play ...f6 next. } ) 7. O-O Nd7 { We arrive at the real starting position of this line. Here White has tried many different moves. It is still unclear what is best. Because the line is so fresh, there is no real established theory yet. } 8. Nbd2 { The second-most popular move. White just develops. It gives Black a nice opportunity, though. } 8... Nh6 $1 { [%cal Rc1h6] [%csl Rd2] Using every available square. } 9. Nb3 Nf7 { [%csl Re5] The knight moves away before White can take it with Bxh6. Now there is pressure on e5. } 10. Re1 { [%cal Ge1e8] Making it risky for Black to take on e5. } ( 10. exf6 Qxf6 { followed by ...Bd6 is nice for Black. } ) 10... g5 $1 { A cool positional move and a very ambitious one, I might add. } 11. Bd2 { The best reaction. The idea is not so much to attack a5, but rather to be able to play Bc3 if the centre opens. } ( 11. exf6 Qxf6 { is good for Black, as you can witness in one of the Model Games (See "Model Games" variation from the PGN). } ) 11... Bg7 { [%csl Re5] Black develops and adds pressure to White's centre. I will stop the line here, but you can find more analysis in the theory section (See "theory section" variation from the PGN). If White takes on f6, Black takes back with the queen with great play. } * 

