1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 $1 { The bishop gets out. Later White's centre can be attacked with ...c5 or ...f6. } 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 { The Short variation. This is the best set-up for White in my opinion, and it is also for a good reason the most popular line in the entire Caro-Kann **3.e5 Bf5** system. White continues to develop before any major decisions are made. Next they can castle short. Black in the meantime must show their chosen set- up and White can respond accordingly. [--] At heart, the Short variation is a positional way of playing for White with quick development and extra space, but White can also strike with c4 and try to fight for the initiative. Because of the enormous popularity of this variation at all levels, I have decided to give two good ways to meet it. One is the principal counterstrike in the centre with } 5... a5 $5 { This surprising move in AlphaZero style has been played several times by Magnus Carlsen and many other top players have used it. The idea is to grab more space on the queenside with ...a4, which Black can afford because the centre is closed and White has no immediate targets. } ( 5... c5 { . This is a big theoretical line, but as far as I can see Black keeps the balance everywhere. It is a very concrete and solid line. [--] My other suggestion is the fresh idea } ) ( 5... a5 $1 $2 { , and this is the move I will concentrate on here in the Quickstarter. But, of course, you can find deep coverage of } ) ( 5... c5 { in the theory section as well, starting here (See "here" variation from the PGN). } ) 6. a4 { The automatic reaction, just stopping all of Black's ideas to expand on the queenside. } 6... f6 { [%csl Re5] Black refrains from the ...**c5** -plan and instead challenges White's centre from the front. It is also possible to start with } ( 6... Nd7 { and then play ...f6 next. } ) 7. O-O Nd7 { We arrive at the real starting position of this line. Here White has tried many different moves. It is still unclear what is best. Because the line is so fresh, there is no real established theory yet. } 8. c4 { The most popular. White is far ahead in development and tries to open the position. } 8... fxe5 9. dxe5 Bc5 { Black activates the bishop. Next up is ...Ne7 and ...O-O with good play, so White has to do something. } 10. Nbd2 { Intending to harass the bishop with Nb3. After } ( 10. cxd5 { both recaptures are playable. I recommend } 10... cxd5 { , as you can see in the theory section (See "theory section" variation from the PGN). } ) ( 10. Nd4 { can be mentioned as well. Black just protects the bishop with } 10... Ne7 { . } ) 10... Ne7 11. Nb3 Ba7 { We've reached a complex position. Black has a good score in the games which have been played here so far, which is a very good sign. Here I will just show the most critical continuation. } 12. Nfd4 Nxe5 { Black has to grab the pawn. } 13. g4 { [%csl Re6] This is the point. The bishop is kicked away and then Nxe6 looks strong. The following moves are pretty forced. } 13... Be4 14. Nxe6 Qd6 15. Nxg7+ Kd7 { A critical position. White has won a pawn, but not for free. Their kingside has been weakened and the knight on g7 is offside. Also, Black's pieces are very active, so at least there is good compensation. The position has been tested in a few games. Armed with an engine it is quite easy to improve Black's play. } 16. Bf4 Nf3+ $1 17. Bxf3 Qxf4 18. Bxe4 Qxe4 { Black has good play. White must play Re1 and give the c-pawn not to be clearly worse. Then anything can happen, but we can be satisfied. In the theory section (See "theory section" variation from the PGN) you can find even deeper analysis, but if you know this much you will do fine! } * 

[Event "A Deep Dive into the Caro-Kann: Advance Variation for Black"]
