[Black "Short Variation: Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 { The Short Variation. } 5... c5 { This is the most principled response. Black immediately starts attacking White's centre. I have always been a fan of this direct way of starting a counterattack. Black has many other options, though. Quite popular are the slightly passive moves For this course I will present an original alternative to the main move } ( 5... Ne7 { and . These moves are very flexible and play can go in several directions afterwards. } ) ( 5... c5 { - } ) ( 5... a5 $1 $2 { . This surprising move in AlphaZero style has been played several times by Magnus Carlsen, and many other top players have used it as well. The idea is to grab more space on the queenside with ...a4, which Black can afford because the centre is closed and White has no immediate targets. } ) 6. Be3 { The main move. Of course, White has other options. It is possible just to castle or to protect the centre with } ( 6. c3 { , but } ) ( 6. Be3 { is the most dangerous. White creates the threat of dxc5. Black has various ways to meet this. } ) 6... cxd4 { The classical response. } ( 6... Qb6 { leads to more complex play. I analyzed it deeply in my book Playing the Caro- Kann, and it is also analyzed in Erwin L'Ami's Caro-Kann LTR. Theoretically it works, but White gets an initiative after } 7. Nc3 { and Black must remember a lot of long, forcing lines. It is perhaps not the most practical line to study. } ) ( 6... Nd7 { Just protecting the c-pawn is an interesting positional choice. After } 7. O-O Ne7 { the other knight is on the way to c6. This looks very playable for Black. In the end I have settled for the more forcing 6...cxd4, which is a direct way to solve all problems. } ) 7. Nxd4 Ne7 { [%cal Ge7f5] Black develops the knight. It is not necessary to move the bishop from f5. If White takes it, we take back with the knight with good play. From f5 the knight also attacks White's bishop on e3. The position after } ( 7... Ne7 { is the starting position of the whole line. White can play the sharp } 8. c4 { or first } ( 8. Nd2 { , or even simply castle } ) ( 8. O-O { . Also quite popular are some active moves like } ) ( 8. Nc3 { or } ) ( 8. Bg5 { . All in all, there is lots of stuff to consider. Basically, Black's position is just very sound, so we can neutralize all aggressive attemps by White. } ) ) * 

