1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 a5 $5 { [%cal Ga5a4] An avant-garde move which really is a sign of the times. Just a few years back, such a move would be more or less unthinkable. It violates the most basic opening principles: it doesn't develop at all nor does it help fight for the centre. What is the purpose of } ( 5... a5 { then? Is it just to be provocative? No! It is a deep strategic concept. Black wants to take space on the queenside with ...a5-a4 next. True, it doesn't help Black's development, but the position is so closed that this doesn't matter at the moment. It will take ages before White is threatening anything. In the meantime, Black improves the position. [--] The theory of } ) ( 5... a5 $1 $2 { is still developing. In my opinion, White's most logical response is to play } 6. a4 { and stop the plan. } ) 6. O-O { The main move } ( 6. a4 { is covered in the next chapter (See "next chapter" variation from the PGN). } ) 6... a4 { White has tried a bunch of different moves here. } 7. Nc3 { The knight is not optimal on c3, but White wants to fight back on the queenside. } 7... Nd7 { The right spot for the knight. } 8. Bd2 { Almost exclusively played. White intends to open the queenside with the break b2-b3. First the knight is protected. This is prophylaxis against ...Bb4 or ...Qa5. As usual, } ( 8. Bd3 { is rather tame. Black should just protect the bishop with } 8... Ne7 { with a fine position. } ) ( 8. Rb1 { could be met by } 8... h6 { , as in the mainline of **8.Bd2**. } ) 8... h6 { [%cal Gg8e7] A flexible move. Keymer has tried to improve with } ( 8... a3 9. b3 h6 { . Objectively the resulting position is probably slightly better for White, but it is still very playable for Black. In the Model Games section you can see the impressive game Kraemer- Keymer (See "Kraemer- Keymer" variation from the PGN), Germany 2025, where Black won a complicated strategic battle. } ) 9. b3 { [%cal Gc3a4] [%csl Ra4] } 9... axb3 { Black simplifies. Carlsen has played } ( 9... b5 { , but I think White is somewhat better after } 10. Bd3 { . } ) 10. axb3 Ne7 11. Rxa8 Qxa8 12. Qa1 { A natural move. White is going for the a-file. } 12... Qb8 { [%cal Gf5c2] [%csl Rc2] It is important not to exchange queens. Now the c2-pawn is hanging. } 13. Rc1 g5 $1 { [%cal Gf7f6] [%csl Ge5] Black starts playing on the kingside. } 14. Na4 { Or } ( 14. h3 Bg7 { and ...f6 will follow, sooner or later. } ) 14... f6 $1 { [%cal Ge7g6] [%csl Re5] Black has good counterplay on the kingside. A sample line goes } 15. exf6 Ng6 $1 { Controlling the e5-square. } 16. Bd3 Bxd3 17. cxd3 Bd6 18. h3 O-O { and Black will win the pawn back with good play. } * 

