s played } ( 9... b5 { , but I think White is somewhat better after } 10. Bd3 { . } ) 10. axb3 Ne7 11. Rxa8 Qxa8 12. Nh4 Bh7 { [%cal Ge7f5] A big improvenment over the game Saric-Gasparyan, EU-ch 2024, that went } ( 12... g5 13. Qa1 $1 Qb8 14. Nxf5 Nxf5 15. Nd1 Be7 16. Bd3 { and White was much better. } ) 13. f4 Nf5 { The most logical continuation. Black can also disturb White with } ( 13... Qa7 $1 $2 { . } ) 14. Nxf5 Bxf5 15. g4 { [%cal Gf4f5] [%csl Rf5] A typical aggressive idea. White will get f4-f5 in. } 15... Bh7 16. f5 Qa7 { [%cal Ga7d4] [%cal Gd7e5] [%csl Rd4] It is important to create some counter-threats. } 17. Be3 Bb4 { [%cal Gd7e5] [%csl Rc3] } ( 17... Nxe5 18. Qa1 $1 { is risky for Black. } ) 18. fxe6 fxe6 { [%cal Gd7e5] [%csl Gc3] } 19. Bd3 $1 { This nice tactic saves White. Please notice that both Nc3 and the e5-pawn were hanging. } 19... Bxd3 { Both } ( 19... Nxe5 20. Bxh7 Rxh7 { and } ) ( 19... Bxc3 20. Bxh7 Rf8 $1 { are also OK for Black. } ) 20. Qxd3 Rf8 { [%cal Gf8f1] The position is balanced. White can easily go astray, as this sample line shows: } 21. Qg6+ Kd8 22. Rxf8+ Nxf8 23. Qxg7 $2 Qa1+ 24. Kg2 Qxc3 { and Black wins. } * 

