[Black "1) Short Variation 5...a5!? - Sidelines"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 a5 $5 { [%cal Ga5a4] An avant-garde move which really is a sign of the times. Just a few years back, such a move would be more or less unthinkable. It violates the most basic opening principles: it doesn't develop at all nor does it help fight for the centre. What is the purpose of } ( 5... a5 { then? Is it just to be provocative? No! It is a deep strategic concept. Black wants to take space on the queenside with ...a5-a4 next. True, it doesn't help Black's development, but the position is so closed that this doesn't matter at the moment. It will take ages before White is threatening anything. In the meantime, Black improves the position. [--] The theory of } ) ( 5... a5 $1 $2 { is still developing. In my opinion, White's most logical response is to play } 6. a4 { and stop the plan. } ) 6. O-O { The main move } ( 6. a4 { is covered in the next chapter (See "next chapter" variation from the PGN). } ) 6... a4 { White has tried a bunch of different moves here. } 7. Nc3 { The knight is not optimal on c3, but White wants to fight back on the queenside. } 7... Nd7 { The right spot for the knight. } 8. Bd2 { Almost exclusively played. White intends to open the queenside with the break b2-b3. First the knight is protected. This is prophylaxis against ...Bb4 or ...Qa5. As usual, } ( 8. Bd3 { is rather tame. Black should just protect the bishop with } 8... Ne7 { with a fine position. } ) ( 8. Rb1 { could be met by } 8... h6 { , as in the mainline of **8.Bd2**. } ) 8... Bb4 { Black can also try this alternative move, in order to get the pieces out. } 9. a3 Ba5 $1 { Keeping the tension. Taking on c3 would give White a free hand. } 10. Bg5 { [%csl Rd8] A good, active move. } 10... f6 { [%csl Re5] [%csl Rg5] } 11. exf6 Ngxf6 { An improvement over Santos Latasa-Kosakowski, 2024, where Black took back with the pawn. After } ( 11... gxf6 { White could have tried } 12. Bd2 $1 { followed by Re1 and perhaps Nh4 with good chances. } ) 12. Nxa4 O-O { [%cal Ga5c7] [%cal Gb7b5] [%cal Gd8e8] Black has good compensation as indicated by Dreev. Is it enough? That is always the question! } * 

