1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 a5 $5 { [%cal Ga5a4] An avant-garde move which really is a sign of the times. Just a few years back, such a move would be more or less unthinkable. It violates the most basic opening principles: it doesn't develop at all nor does it help fight for the centre. What is the purpose of } ( 5... a5 { then? Is it just to be provocative? No! It is a deep strategic concept. Black wants to take space on the queenside with ...a5-a4 next. True, it doesn't help Black's development, but the position is so closed that this doesn't matter at the moment. It will take ages before White is threatening anything. In the meantime, Black improves the position. [--] The theory of } ) ( 5... a5 $1 $2 { is still developing. In my opinion, White's most logical response is to play } 6. a4 { and stop the plan. } ) 6. O-O { The main move } ( 6. a4 { is covered in the next chapter (See "next chapter" variation from the PGN). } ) 6... a4 { White has tried a bunch of different moves here. } 7. Re1 { A kind of waiting move. The rook doesn't do much on e1. } 7... h6 { [%cal Gf5h7] A nice move that controls the g5-square and, more importantly, gives the bishop a retreat on h7. } 8. Nbd2 Ne7 9. Nf1 { Both sides start maneuvering. } 9... Nd7 10. Ng3 Bh7 { [%cal Ge7f5] [%csl Gf5] } 11. Bd3 { The Caro-Kann bishop is very strong, so it makes sense for White to exchange it. } 11... Bxd3 12. Qxd3 c5 { [%cal Ge7c6] } 13. Be3 { More solid is } ( 13. c3 { , but Black is fine after } 13... Nc6 { . } ) 13... Nc6 14. c4 { A standard move in the Short Variation. Again, } ( 14. c3 { is more solid. } ) 14... cxd4 15. Bxd4 { This happened in Zhigalko-Carlsen, blitz 2024. Here I like } 15... Nb6 { [%cal Gb6d5] [%cal Gb6c4] [%csl Gd5] } 16. cxd5 { Or } ( 16. Bxb6 Qxb6 17. cxd5 Nb4 { followed by ...Nxd5 with good play. } ) 16... Nxd5 { [%cal Gf8e7] [%cal Ge8g8] [%csl Gd5] Black is fine with the strong knight on d5. } * 

