1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 a5 $5 { [%cal Ga5a4] An avant-garde move which really is a sign of the times. Just a few years back, such a move would be more or less unthinkable. It violates the most basic opening principles: it doesn't develop at all nor does it help fight for the centre. What is the purpose of } ( 5... a5 { then? Is it just to be provocative? No! It is a deep strategic concept. Black wants to take space on the queenside with ...a5-a4 next. True, it doesn't help Black's development, but the position is so closed that this doesn't matter at the moment. It will take ages before White is threatening anything. In the meantime, Black improves the position. [--] The theory of } ) ( 5... a5 $1 $2 { is still developing. In my opinion, White's most logical response is to play } 6. a4 { and stop the plan. } ) 6. O-O { The main move } ( 6. a4 { is covered in the next chapter (See "next chapter" variation from the PGN). } ) 6... a4 { White has tried a bunch of different moves here. } 7. Nbd2 { Perhaps the best move. } 7... Nd7 8. c3 h6 9. Ne1 Ne7 10. Bd3 { White figures that some exchanges won't hurt. The extra space they have is a long-term asset. } 10... c5 11. Ndf3 Qb6 { [%cal Gb6b2] [%csl Rd4] A good positional move that puts pressure on the d4-pawn and ties White's bishop to the defense of b2. The continuation Also } ( 11... Qc7 12. Nh4 Bxd3 13. Nxd3 c4 14. Nb4 { happened in Nepomniachtchi-Duda, rapid 2025. Here } 14... g5 $1 15. Nf3 Ng6 { would have been good for Black. } ) ( 11... Be4 $1 $2 { could be tried. } ) 12. Rb1 { Protecting b2. } 12... Bxd3 13. Nxd3 Nc6 { [%cal Gc5d4] [%cal Gf8e7] Black is fine. A sample line goes } 14. Be3 cxd4 15. cxd4 Nb4 16. Nxb4 Bxb4 17. h4 $1 $2 O-O 18. h5 Be7 { with a sound position for Black. } * 

