1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 a5 $5 { [%cal Ga5a4] An avant-garde move which really is a sign of the times. Just a few years back, such a move would be more or less unthinkable. It violates the most basic opening principles: it doesn't develop at all nor does it help fight for the centre. What is the purpose of } ( 5... a5 { then? Is it just to be provocative? No! It is a deep strategic concept. Black wants to take space on the queenside with ...a5-a4 next. True, it doesn't help Black's development, but the position is so closed that this doesn't matter at the moment. It will take ages before White is threatening anything. In the meantime, Black improves the position. [--] The theory of } ) ( 5... a5 $1 $2 { is still developing. In my opinion, White's most logical response is to play } 6. a4 { and stop the plan. } ) 6. O-O { The main move } ( 6. a4 { is covered in the next chapter (See "next chapter" variation from the PGN). } ) 6... a4 { White has tried a bunch of different moves here. } 7. c4 { Striking in the centre is logical, but Black gets the d5-square. } ( 7. a3 { stops the black a-pawn, but after } 7... Nd7 { Black is fine. A typical battle will be similar to the other lines we have seen. } ) ( 7. Bd3 { tries to exchange Black's strong Caro-Kann bishop. It's a typical idea we will see many times in this course. Here it is rather tame and it shouldn't bother us. 7...Ne7Ν is a simple response. Now we can always take back on f5 with the knight. Black has no real problems. } ) 7... dxc4 8. Bxc4 { 8...Ne7Ν is a new move. This just shows how few games there have been. 9.Nc3 } 8... Nd7 { [%cal Gd7b6] Intending ...Nb6. } ( 8... Nd7 { This is a flexible alternative. White can't take the pawn with 10.Nxa4 because of 10...b5 , and after something like 9... Nd7 10.Bd3 Bxd3 11.Qxd3 Nd5 Black is fine. } ) 9. Nc3 Nb6 { [%cal Gb6c4] [%csl Rc4] Gaining a tempo on White's bishop. } 10. Bd3 { Exchanging bishops makes some sense. } 10... Ne7 11. Bg5 { Intending Nxf5, when Black is forced to take back with the e-pawn. } 11... Qd7 $5 { [%cal Rg5d8] The most interesting. } ( 11... Bxd3 12. Qxd3 h6 { is also fine. } ) 12. Bxe7 Bxe7 { In a blitz game Black played } ( 12... Bxd3 { . This should have lost after } 13. Bxf8 Bxf1 14. Bc5 $1 { , hitting the knight. } ) 13. Bxf5 exf5 { [%cal Ge8g8] [%cal Gd7e6] [%csl Rd4] Black is fine. We can castle and put the queen on e6. In the long run White's d4-pawn and their entire queenside might be vulnerable. } * 

