1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 a5 $5 { [%cal Ga5a4] An avant-garde move which really is a sign of the times. Just a few years back, such a move would be more or less unthinkable. It violates the most basic opening principles: it doesn't develop at all nor does it help fight for the centre. What is the purpose of } ( 5... a5 { then? Is it just to be provocative? No! It is a deep strategic concept. Black wants to take space on the queenside with ...a5-a4 next. True, it doesn't help Black's development, but the position is so closed that this doesn't matter at the moment. It will take ages before White is threatening anything. In the meantime, Black improves the position. [--] The theory of } ) ( 5... a5 $1 $2 { is still developing. In my opinion, White's most logical response is to play } 6. a4 { and stop the plan. } ) 6. O-O { The main move } ( 6. a4 { is covered in the next chapter (See "next chapter" variation from the PGN). } ) 6... a4 { White has tried a bunch of different moves here. } 7. c4 { Striking in the centre is logical, but Black gets the d5-square. } ( 7. a3 { stops the black a-pawn, but after } 7... Nd7 { Black is fine. A typical battle will be similar to the other lines we have seen. } ) ( 7. Bd3 { tries to exchange Black's strong Caro-Kann bishop. It's a typical idea we will see many times in this course. Here it is rather tame and it shouldn't bother us. 7...Ne7Ν is a simple response. Now we can always take back on f5 with the knight. Black has no real problems. } ) 7... dxc4 8. Bxc4 { 8...Ne7Ν is a new move. This just shows how few games there have been. 9.Nc3 } 8... Nd7 { [%cal Gd7b6] Intending ...Nb6. } ( 8... Nd7 { This is a flexible alternative. White can't take the pawn with 10.Nxa4 because of 10...b5 , and after something like 9... Nd7 10.Bd3 Bxd3 11.Qxd3 Nd5 Black is fine. } ) 9. Nc3 Nb6 { [%cal Gb6c4] [%csl Rc4] Gaining a tempo on White's bishop. } 10. Be2 { Keeping the bishop. } 10... Ne7 11. Nh4 { [%csl Rf5] A typical motif in the Short Variation. White goes for the strong f5-bishop. It loses time, though, and the d4-pawn lacks some protection. } 11... h6 { [%cal Gf5h7] Forcing White to take. Otherwise the bishop drops back to h7. } 12. Nxf5 Nxf5 { [%csl Rd4] Attacking d4. } 13. Be3 a3 { [%cal Gf8e7] [%cal Gf8b4] [%cal Ge8g8] [%csl Rb2] A nice move that softens White's queenside. Black has good play. • Vachier Lagrave-Carlsen, rapid 2023 continued • } 14. Rb1 ( 14. b3 Bb4 { is no problem. Black can even take on c3. } ) 14... Be7 15. Bd3 Nxe3 16. fxe3 O-O { with equal play. } * 

[Event "A Deep Dive into the Caro-Kann: Advance Variation for Black"]
[Site "Short 5...a5 6.a4 Mainline: 8.Nbd2 #1"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Short 5...a5 6.a4 Mainline: 8.Nbd2 #1"]
[Black "2) Short Variation 5...a5!? - 6.a4 Mainline"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 a5 $5 6. a4 { White blocks the queenside. This is the most natural response to **5...a5** , and it kind of mirrors the positions with h4-h5 that we will come across again and again in this course. } ( 6. a4 { , Black usually starts with } 6... Nd7 { which transposes to our mainline after } ( 6... f6 { is rare, it is a well-known idea! } ) 7. O-O f6 { , so although } ) 6... f6 { [%csl Re5] This was a novelty back when I researched this line. It is quite an obvious move. Black starts attacking the important e5-pawn hoping that White will be forced to take on f6, which would ease Black's game. In the few games that have reached the position after } 7. O-O { White doesn't have that many constructive moves. } ( 7. Nbd2 { can be met by } 7... Nh6 $1 { , exploiting the fact that White's c1-bishop has been blocked. Next Black will play ...Nd7 and ...Nf7 to put the e5-pawn under severe pressure. } ) 7... Nd7 { We arrive at the real starting position of this line. Here White has tried many different moves. It is still unclear what is best. Because the line is so fresh, there is no real established theory yet. } 8. Nbd2 { The second-most popular move. White just develops. It gives Black a nice opportunity, though. } 8... Nh6 $1 { [%cal Rc1h6] [%csl Rd2] Using every available square. } 9. Re1 fxe5 10. Nxe5 ( 10. dxe5 Be7 { is fine for Black. } ) 10... Nxe5 11. dxe5 Bg6 { [%cal Gh6f5] Regrouping nicely. } 12. Nb3 Nf5 { [%cal Gf8e7] [%cal Ge8g8] Black had no problems in Petrov-Dautov, 2023. Against quiet play we will finish our development with ...Be7 and ...O-O. } * 

