1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 a5 $5 6. a4 { White blocks the queenside. This is the most natural response to **5...a5** , and it kind of mirrors the positions with h4-h5 that we will come across again and again in this course. } ( 6. a4 { , Black usually starts with } 6... Nd7 { which transposes to our mainline after } ( 6... f6 { is rare, it is a well-known idea! } ) 7. O-O f6 { , so although } ) 6... f6 { [%csl Re5] This was a novelty back when I researched this line. It is quite an obvious move. Black starts attacking the important e5-pawn hoping that White will be forced to take on f6, which would ease Black's game. In the few games that have reached the position after } 7. O-O { White doesn't have that many constructive moves. } ( 7. Nbd2 { can be met by } 7... Nh6 $1 { , exploiting the fact that White's c1-bishop has been blocked. Next Black will play ...Nd7 and ...Nf7 to put the e5-pawn under severe pressure. } ) 7... Nd7 { We arrive at the real starting position of this line. Here White has tried many different moves. It is still unclear what is best. Because the line is so fresh, there is no real established theory yet. } 8. Nbd2 { The second-most popular move. White just develops. It gives Black a nice opportunity, though. } 8... Nh6 $1 { [%cal Rc1h6] [%csl Rd2] Using every available square. } 9. Nb3 Nf7 { The knight moves away before White can take it with Bxh6. Now there is pressure on e5. } 10. Re1 { [%cal Ge1e8] Making it risky for Black to take on e5. } ( 10. exf6 Qxf6 { is nice for Black. } ) 10... g5 $1 { A cool positional move and a very ambitious one, I might add. The more slow } ( 10... Be7 { is playable, but White can take on f6 and play Bd3 with easier play. } ) 11. exf6 Qxf6 { As usual exf6 helps Black's pieces to achieve active squares. } 12. Bd3 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 g4 14. Nh4 { A spectacular piece sacrifice. After the natural } ( 14. Nfd2 h5 { Black has the initiative. See the Model Game Liang- Ghasi (See "Liang- Ghasi" variation from the PGN), 2023. } ) 14... Be7 { [%cal Gf6h4] [%csl Rh4] After } ( 14... Qxh4 15. Rxe6+ { White gets a strong attack. Now after first **14...Be7** we are threatening to take, though. } ) 15. g3 e5 { [%cal Gd7e5] [%cal Gf7e5] [%csl Gd5] [%csl Ge5] Black liberates the position with good play. } * 

