1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 a5 $5 6. a4 { White blocks the queenside. This is the most natural response to **5...a5** , and it kind of mirrors the positions with h4-h5 that we will come across again and again in this course. } ( 6. a4 { , Black usually starts with } 6... Nd7 { which transposes to our mainline after } ( 6... f6 { is rare, it is a well-known idea! } ) 7. O-O f6 { , so although } ) 6... f6 { [%csl Re5] This was a novelty back when I researched this line. It is quite an obvious move. Black starts attacking the important e5-pawn hoping that White will be forced to take on f6, which would ease Black's game. In the few games that have reached the position after } 7. O-O { White doesn't have that many constructive moves. } ( 7. Nbd2 { can be met by } 7... Nh6 $1 { , exploiting the fact that White's c1-bishop has been blocked. Next Black will play ...Nd7 and ...Nf7 to put the e5-pawn under severe pressure. } ) 7... Nd7 { We arrive at the real starting position of this line. Here White has tried many different moves. It is still unclear what is best. Because the line is so fresh, there is no real established theory yet. } 8. Bf4 { The bishop controls e5, so we shouldn't take. } 8... Ne7 { Or } ( 8... g5 $1 $2 9. Bg3 h5 { , using the bishop as a target. } 10. exf6 Qxf6 11. Ne5 Qh6 12. Nxd7 Kxd7 { This has been played with success by black players, but I don't like that White's bishop has the e5-square. } ) 9. Bg3 { This prophylactic move is too slow. } 9... fxe5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. Bxe5 { White can't keep the bishop on this square. } 11... Ng6 { [%cal Gf8d6] [%cal Ge8g8] Now Black's pieces jump into the game. } 12. Bh5 Bd6 { [%cal Ge8g8] Black had good play in Grigorjev-Eljanov, blitz 2024. } * 

