1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 a5 $5 6. a4 { White blocks the queenside. This is the most natural response to **5...a5** , and it kind of mirrors the positions with h4-h5 that we will come across again and again in this course. } ( 6. a4 { , Black usually starts with } 6... Nd7 { which transposes to our mainline after } ( 6... f6 { is rare, it is a well-known idea! } ) 7. O-O f6 { , so although } ) 6... f6 { [%csl Re5] This was a novelty back when I researched this line. It is quite an obvious move. Black starts attacking the important e5-pawn hoping that White will be forced to take on f6, which would ease Black's game. In the few games that have reached the position after } 7. O-O { White doesn't have that many constructive moves. } ( 7. Nbd2 { can be met by } 7... Nh6 $1 { , exploiting the fact that White's c1-bishop has been blocked. Next Black will play ...Nd7 and ...Nf7 to put the e5-pawn under severe pressure. } ) 7... Nd7 { We arrive at the real starting position of this line. Here White has tried many different moves. It is still unclear what is best. Because the line is so fresh, there is no real established theory yet. } 8. c3 { Solid. } 8... fxe5 9. dxe5 Bc5 10. Nbd2 { The most flexible move. } 10... Ne7 11. Nd4 { White must play very forcefully. } ( 11. Nb3 Ba7 12. Nbd4 O-O { gave Black good play in Pyrig-Iturrizaga, 2025. } ) 11... Bxd4 { Grabbing the pawn doesn't work: } ( 11... Nxe5 12. g4 $1 { and White was winning in Bulmaga-Hoanca, 2024. } ) 12. cxd4 O-O { [%cal Gc6c5] Black is positionally fine. The plan is to get ...c5 in. } * 

