1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 c5 { Black immediately attacks White's centre. This is a very principled move, and it has always been one of the most important lines in the **5.Be2** Short variation. Now after } ( 5... c5 { the big mainline is } 6. Be3 { , but also } ( 6. c3 { and } ) ( 6. O-O Nc6 7. c3 { have been popular. In this chapter we will have a quick look at some more rare tries on move 6. } ) ) 6. Nc3 { White introduces some tricky piece play. The knight is bad on c3, blocking the c-pawn, so Black should be able to take advantage of it. } 6... Nc6 7. Be3 { Trying to protect the centre. } ( 7. O-O Bg4 { is good for Black. } ) 7... Bg4 { [%cal Gg4f3] [%csl Gd4] Threatening to eliminate a key defender of d4. } 8. O-O ( 8. dxc5 Bxf3 9. Bxf3 Nge7 { followed by ...Nf5 looks great for Black. } ) 8... Bxf3 9. Bxf3 cxd4 10. Bxd4 Nge7 { [%cal Ge7g6] [%cal Ge7f5] The simplest. Black is already better. The knight can go to f5 or g6 next. I have played } ( 10... Nh6 11. Ne2 Nf5 { , which is also ok. Ziska-Schandorff, Denmark 2013. } ) * 

