1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 c5 { Black immediately attacks White's centre. This is a very principled move, and it has always been one of the most important lines in the **5.Be2** Short variation. Now after } ( 5... c5 { the big mainline is } 6. Be3 { , but also } ( 6. c3 { and } ) ( 6. O-O Nc6 7. c3 { have been popular. In this chapter we will have a quick look at some more rare tries on move 6. } ) ) 6. dxc5 { Releasing the tension gives Black easy play. } 6... Bxc5 7. O-O Nc6 8. a3 { Intending to expand on the queenside with b4 and Bb2. Against more slow play Black will just develop with ...Nge7 with a nice position. } 8... a6 { It's always good to control the b5-square. } 9. b4 Ba7 10. Bb2 Nge7 { [%cal Gd8c7] [%cal Ge8g8] Black is fine. Next we will probably castle and play ...Qc7 with a harmonious position. Blocking the queenside with ...b7-b5 is also an option, and a further point of playing ...a6. After } ( 10... Nge7 { a sample line goes } 11. Nh4 Be4 12. Nd2 Ng6 { This was Fernandez-Jobava, Spain 2023. After } 13. Nxe4 dxe4 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. Qxd8+ Rxd8 16. Rad1 Ke7 { Black is much better. We can play ...e3 or ...Bd4 and White's e5-pawn is really weak. } ) * 

