1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 c5 6. c3 { A solid move. White reinforces their centre and tries to hang onto the extra space. } 6... Nc6 7. Be3 Qb6 $1 { [%csl Rb2] The bishop is missing on c1. } 8. Qd2 ( 8. Qb3 c4 $1 9. Qxb6 axb6 10. Nbd2 b5 { is already good for Black. } ) ( 8. O-O { has never been played before, but might work. } 8... Qxb2 9. dxc5 Nge7 $1 { with an interesting position that needs testing. Just don't take the rook: } ( 9... Qxa1 10. Qb3 { is already winning for White. } ) ) 8... Bg4 { A very natural move. We will see it many times in this chapter. The d4-pawn becomes a target, and now the g8-knight can get to f5. } 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Bxf3 cxd4 11. cxd4 Nge7 { [%cal Ge7f5] [%csl Rd4] Followed by ...**Nf5** with a good position. The wild } 12. g4 { weakens White's position a lot, and Black can then play the knight to g6 with } 12... Ng6 { instead. } * 

