1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 { Here the by far most played move is } 7. Nc3 { Blocking the c-pawn is strategically risky for White. } ( 7. c3 { , when } 7... cxd4 { will send us to the 6.c3 chapter (See "the 6.c3 chapter" variation from the PGN). In the current chapter I will look at White's other possibilities in the position after 6... c5 6.O-O Nc6 . } ) 7... Bg4 { A standard move, immediately putting pressure on White's centre. } ( 7... cxd4 8. Nb5 { is White's idea, so 7. Nc3 7...a6!? would also make a lot of sense. } ) 8. Ng5 { This has never been played before, but it is the only interesting move. Otherwise, Black has easy play. For example } ( 8. dxc5 Bxf3 $1 $2 9. Bxf3 Bxc5 { and e5 is weak. } ) 8... Bxe2 9. Nxe2 Nh6 { [%cal Gh6f5] Going to **f5**. The other way, } ( 9... Nge7 10. c3 Nf5 { , is also good. } ) 10. Nf3 Nf5 11. c3 Be7 { [%cal Ge8g8] It is possible to include } ( 11... cxd4 { , but there is no reason to release the tension just yet. After } ) ( 11... Be7 { Black is doing really well, positionally speaking. The sharp try } 12. g4 Nh4 13. Nxh4 Bxh4 14. dxc5 { can be met by } 14... Be7 15. Be3 Nxe5 { and Black is better due to the superior structure. } ) * 

