1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 { Here the by far most played move is } 7. Be3 ( 7. c3 { , when } 7... cxd4 { will send us to the 6.c3 chapter (See "the 6.c3 chapter" variation from the PGN). In the current chapter I will look at White's other possibilities in the position after 6... c5 6.O-O Nc6 . } ) 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nxd4 { Here } ( 8... Nge7 { transposes to the line (See "the line" variation from the PGN) 6... c5 6.Be3 \- see Chapter 7. } ) 9. Qxd4 { Activating the queen is not without risk. After } ( 9. Bxd4 Ne7 { White is forced to do something before Black plays ...Nc6 and ...Be7 with a good game. So they'll probably play } 10. c4 { and after } 10... dxc4 { we have transposed to the line (See "the line" variation from the PGN) **7.c4**. } ) 9... Ne7 10. Qa4+ Nc6 11. c4 ( 11. Bb5 Qc8 { transposes to the line (See "the line" variation from the PGN) **10.Bb5+**. } ) 11... d4 $1 { [%csl Re3] Black can already play for an advantage. } 12. Rd1 Bc5 { [%csl Gd4] Protecting the pawn with good play. } 13. b4 { White can try this active move. } 13... Qh4 $1 { [%cal Gd4e3] A brilliant refutation. } 14. g3 ( 14. bxc5 dxe3 15. fxe3 Qg5 { is horrible for White. } ) 14... Qe4 15. Bd3 { This was Yip-Munguntuul, Olympiad 2024. } 15... Qg4 $1 { [%cal Gd4e3] [%cal Gc5b4] This move would have given Black a winning position. A fantastic line goes } 16. Bxf5 Qxf5 17. Bd2 Be7 18. f4 O-O-O $1 $2 19. b5 Bc5 $1 { The start of a beautiful attack. } 20. bxc6 d3+ 21. Kg2 Qe4+ 22. Kh3 g5 $1 23. Qb5 Bb6 $1 24. fxg5 Qf5+ 25. Kg2 Qf2+ 26. Kh3 h5 $1 27. gxh6 Rxh6+ $1 28. Bxh6 Rh8 29. cxb7+ Kb8 { and White is forced to give the queen with Qe8+ in order not to be mated in a few moves. } * 

[Event "A Deep Dive into the Caro-Kann: Advance Variation for Black"]
[Site "Short 5...c5 6.Be3: 8.Bg5 #1"]
