[White "Short 5...c5 6.Be3: 8.Bg5 #1"]
[Black "6) Short Variation 5...c5 - 6.Be3, Rare 8th Moves"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 c5 6. Be3 { The big mainline. White overprotects the centre and is ready to perhaps take on c5. At the same time, the strike c2-c4 is held in reserve. } 6... cxd4 { The safest. The sharp } ( 6... Qb6 { seems playable too. Usually play continues } 7. Nc3 Nc6 8. O-O Qxb2 9. Qe1 cxd4 10. Bxd4 Nxd4 11. Nxd4 Bb4 12. Rb1 Bxc3 13. Rxb2 Bxe1 14. Rxe1 b6 { when Black is a pawn up, but White has a strong initiative and a good score in practice. Engines keep the balance somehow, but I would rather not go in that direction. } ) 7. Nxd4 Ne7 { [%cal Ge7f5] Protecting the bishop on **f5**. This is the first important branch of the **6.Be3** mainline. White has three popular moves here: } 8. Bg5 { Pinning the knight and intending Nxf5. Of course, moving the bishop twice so early goes against basic opening principles. } ( 8. O-O { , just getting the king to safety; } ) ( 8. c4 { , trying to open the position; and } ) ( 8. Nd2 { , the most flexible. [--] In this chapter we will consider some minor alternatives that White has to these three main moves. } ) 8... Qd7 $1 { [%cal Ge7f5] [%cal Gb8c6] [%csl Gf5] Breaking the pin and forcing White to part with the bishop if they want to damage our structure. } 9. Bxe7 { Otherwise White's play doesn't make sense. } 9... Bxe7 10. Nxf5 exf5 { Black is fine despite the doubled pawns. } 11. Bf3 { [%csl Rd5] Hitting **d5**. Regrouping with } ( 11. Nd2 Nc6 12. Nf3 { gives White nothing after } 12... a6 { , covering the b5-square. Next up is ...O-O and ...Rad8, with a fine position for Black as has been confirmed in a couple of email games. } ) 11... Qb5 $1 { [%csl Rb2] Counterattacking **b2**. I have played } ( 11... d4 12. O-O O-O { , which is also fine for Black, Pilgaard-Schandorff, Denmark 2010. } ) 12. Qxd5 Qxb2 13. O-O { Not } ( 13. Qxb7 Bb4+ $1 14. Ke2 O-O { and Black wins. } ) 13... Nc6 { [%cal Gb2a1] [%cal Gb2e5] [%cal Ge8g8] Black is doing well. } 14. Nd2 Rd8 { Or } ( 14... Qxe5 15. Qxe5 Nxe5 16. Bxb7 Rb8 $10 { . } ) 15. Qb3 Qxb3 16. Nxb3 { This was Mamedov-Rodshtein, 2008. } 16... Nxe5 { A simple solution, just intending to castle next. } 17. Bxb7 O-O { [%csl Rc2] I even slightly prefer Black. White's c-pawn is more of a weakness than a strength. } * 

