1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 c5 6. Be3 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Ne7 8. O-O { A natural move. } 8... Nbc6 9. Bb5 { White needs to play actively and strive for the initiative. After a soft move like } ( 9. f4 { Black is very comfortable after } 9... Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Nc6 { . } ) 9... a6 { Forcing White to make a decision. } 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 { The fighting option. } ( 10... Nxc6 { allows } 11. Nxf5 exf5 12. c3 { , which is playable for Black after } 12... Be7 { , but White has a clear plus score from this position. } ) 11. c4 { Almost exclusively played. } 11... Qd7 { Black has a good structure and keeps everything under control. } 12. Nc3 dxc4 $1 { [%cal Ge7d5] This is forced. Black needs to get some squares for the pieces. Now the knight can go to d5. } 13. Nxf5 { This allows a queen exchange. } 13... Qxd1 14. Nxd1 { Taking with a rook is no better, and after the intermediate move } ( 14. Nxg7+ { we just recapture } 14... Bxg7 { and next win back the pawn on e5 with a fine game. } ) 14... Nxf5 15. Rc1 { The point of Nxd1. White attacks Black's c-pawn and the bishop is protected. } 15... O-O-O { Black could even sac a pawn: } ( 15... Be7 $1 $2 16. Rxc4 O-O 17. Rxc6 Rfc8 18. Rxc8+ Rxc8 { Black is ready to invade with the rook on c2. } 19. g4 Nxe3 20. Nxe3 Rc5 { Hitting e5. } 21. f4 g5 { White can't keep the centre and if anyone is better, it is Black. } ) 16. Rxc4 Kb7 { [%cal Gf8e7] The position is equal. White can't put pressure on c6, and we will develop with ...Be7 next. } * 

