1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 c5 6. Be3 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Ne7 8. c4 { An attractive move that leads to an immediate confrontation in the centre. } 8... Nbc6 9. Qa4 { White must keep up the pressure. } 9... a6 $1 { The standard move. Now White has tried several things without getting much. } ( 9... dxc4 { is a computer favourite. The mainline goes } 10. Na3 Qa5+ 11. Qxa5 Nxa5 12. Nxc4 Nxc4 13. Bxc4 a6 { and Black is ok. } ) 10. cxd5 b5 $1 { [%csl Ra4] You could take back on d5, but this is nice. } 11. Nxc6 { The most challenging. } ( 11. Qd1 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Nxd5 { is comfortable for Black. } ) 11... Nxc6 12. Qf4 { The queen is active on this square. } 12... Nb4 $1 { [%cal Gb4c2] [%cal Gb4d5] Another nice intermediate move. } 13. O-O Nxd5 $1 { Black is fine after Please avoid } ( 13... Nxd5 { . } ) ( 13... Nc2 14. Nc3 Nxa1 15. Rxa1 { and Black won't survive. } ) 14. Qg3 Nxe3 15. fxe3 $5 { The most dangerous try. } ( 15. Qxe3 Rc8 { is fine for Black. } ) 15... Bg6 { [%cal Gf8e7] [%cal Gf8c5] Preparing to develop the dark-squared bishop. } 16. a4 { White must be quick in order to create something. } 16... bxa4 17. Bd1 { Very cunning. White will take on a4 with check before we can spirit our king away. } 17... Bc5 18. Bxa4+ Kf8 { [%cal Gf8g8] [%cal Gh7h6] [%cal Gg8h7] [%csl Re3] [%csl Re5] However, it turns out that we are perfectly safe. Our bishop pair and White's bad pawns might tell in the long run. A sample line goes } 19. Na3 Kg8 20. Nc4 h6 { when the king will go to h7 and the rook in the corner can be developed with a good game. } * 

