1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 c5 6. Be3 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Ne7 8. c4 { An attractive move that leads to an immediate confrontation in the centre. } 8... Nbc6 9. Qa4 { White must keep up the pressure. } 9... a6 $1 { The standard move. Now White has tried several things without getting much. } ( 9... dxc4 { is a computer favourite. The mainline goes } 10. Na3 Qa5+ 11. Qxa5 Nxa5 12. Nxc4 Nxc4 13. Bxc4 a6 { and Black is ok. } ) 10. Nc3 dxc4 { Black must release the tension. } 11. O-O-O Qa5 { Going for an ending. } 12. Qxa5 ( 12. Nxf5 Nxf5 13. Qxa5 Nxa5 { transposes. } ) 12... Nxa5 13. Nxf5 Nxf5 14. Bb6 Nc6 15. f4 { [%csl Rc4] [%csl Ge5] Protecting the important e5-pawn. It seems that White will win the pawn back on c4 and have a strong bishop pair. Black needs to react with very precise play. } 15... Be7 { [%cal Gg7g5] The most played move } ( 15... Rc8 { is also fine. Also there the idea is to seek quick counterplay with ...g7-g5. } ) 16. Bxc4 { Taking the pawn back. } ( 16. g3 $1 $2 { has never been played. I like } 16... g5 $1 17. Bxc4 Bd8 $1 $2 { with an interesting position in which Black is not worse. } ) 16... g5 $1 17. g4 { The sharpest reply. } ( 17. g3 { has been covered via the **16.g3** move order. } ) 17... Nh4 18. f5 { White continues with aggressive moves. } ( 18. fxg5 Bxg5+ { is no problem for Black. } ) 18... Nxe5 { [%csl Rc4] We must accept the bait. } 19. Bb3 exf5 20. gxf5 Rc8 { Pinning White's knight. } 21. Kb1 O-O { [%cal Ge7d8] [%cal Gd8b6] We've arrived at a really interesting position. It is balanced, but very complicated. An email game continued } 22. Rhf1 { Bd8Ν Trying to improve on **22...h6** from that game. 23.Be3 } 22... Nc4 23. Bd4 { Re8 25.Nd5 } 23... h5 24. f6 Kh7 { and next the king can go to h6. Black is still a pawn up. It is quite unclear. } * 

