1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 c5 6. Be3 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Ne7 8. Nd2 { [%cal Gd2f3] This is a good move. White concentrates the pieces in the centre and keeps the break c2-c4 in reserve. } 8... Nbc6 { The little move } ( 8... a6 $1 $2 { prevents any Bb5 ideas and could be considered. Then again, we are not really afraid of Bb5, so... } ) 9. Bb5 { As usual, this is an option worth checking. } 9... a6 { [%csl Rb5] Clarifying the situation. } 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. b4 { [%csl Gc5] Taking control over the c5-square. We saw the same idea after **8.O-O**. } 11... Bg6 { [%cal Ge7f5] Black keeps control. More popular is to go after the **e5** -pawn with } ( 11... Qc7 12. O-O Qxe5 13. c4 { when White has compensation for the pawn, but Black should be ok. } ) 12. O-O { It's important that After the mentioned } ( 12. c3 Nf5 { transposes after } 13. Nxf5 ( 13. Nxc6 { is bad for White. After } 13... Qd7 14. Nd4 Nxe3 15. fxe3 Be7 { Black has great play for the pawn. The bishops can be activated on g5 and d3, the c3-pawn can be attacked on the c-file, and e5 is chronically weak. } ) 13... Bxf5 14. O-O { , because } ) ( 12. c3 Nf5 13. Nxf5 Bxf5 { , instead of transposing with } 14. O-O { , White does have the independent possibility of } ( 14. Nb3 { . However, here Black has the cool response } 14... Qc7 15. f4 a5 $1 { , when after } 16. Nxa5 c5 { Black has great positional compensation for the pawn. } ) ) 12... Nf5 13. Nxf5 Bxf5 14. c3 { Protecting b4 and covering the d4-square. However, White does not have enough time to conquer the c5-square with Nb3. } 14... Qc7 { [%csl Re5] Hitting e5. } 15. f4 c5 { The freeing break. The best White can get is an ending with a temporary extra pawn. } 16. Qa4+ Qd7 17. Qxd7+ Kxd7 18. bxc5 Kc7 $1 { Leaving the d-file. } 19. Nf3 Be7 20. Nd4 g6 $1 { [%cal Gg6f5] Not allowing White to play f4-f5. } 21. Nxf5 gxf5 { [%cal Ga8b8] [%cal Gh8c8] [%csl Rc5] The position is balanced. Two sample lines: • • } 22. Kf2 ( 22. Rab1 Rhb8 23. Kf2 Rb5 24. a4 Ra5 { is similar. } ) 22... Rab8 23. Rab1 Rhc8 24. Kf3 Kd7 { and the c5-pawn is in trouble. } * 

