1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 c5 6. Be3 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Ne7 8. Nd2 { [%cal Gd2f3] This is a good move. White concentrates the pieces in the centre and keeps the break c2-c4 in reserve. } 8... Nbc6 { The little move } ( 8... a6 $1 $2 { prevents any Bb5 ideas and could be considered. Then again, we are not really afraid of Bb5, so... } ) 9. N2f3 { The real point of **8.Nd2**. White keeps a knight on d4 this way. } 9... Be4 { [%cal Ge4f3] A nice move. Black secures the bishop and prepares to take on f3. } 10. O-O Bxf3 { Safe, sound and easy to remember! Some strong players have experimented with } ( 10... a6 { , but after } 11. Rc1 { intending c4 White has some initiative, although Black seems to be ok. Anyway, there is no reason to go into this. } ) 11. Nxf3 Qc7 { [%csl Re5] Now e5 is a target. } 12. c4 { The direct push is much easier to meet than if White first moves the rook to c1. } 12... dxc4 13. Bxc4 Nf5 { [%cal Gf8e7] [%cal Ge8g8] } 14. Qe2 { The most played move. } 14... Be7 { Black can take on e3, but also just develop. } 15. Rac1 O-O { [%cal Gf8d8] [%cal Gf5e3] Black is solid and fine. A sample line goes } 16. a3 Rfd8 17. Bd3 Nxe3 18. Qxe3 Qb6 $1 19. Qxb6 axb6 { with an equal ending. There are some winning chances for Black because several white pawns are stuck on dark squares and can be attacked by our bishop. } * 

