1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 c5 6. Be3 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Ne7 8. Nd2 { [%cal Gd2f3] This is a good move. White concentrates the pieces in the centre and keeps the break c2-c4 in reserve. } 8... Nbc6 { The little move } ( 8... a6 $1 $2 { prevents any Bb5 ideas and could be considered. Then again, we are not really afraid of Bb5, so... } ) 9. N2f3 { The real point of **8.Nd2**. White keeps a knight on d4 this way. } 9... Be4 { [%cal Ge4f3] A nice move. Black secures the bishop and prepares to take on f3. } 10. O-O Bxf3 { Safe, sound and easy to remember! Some strong players have experimented with } ( 10... a6 { , but after } 11. Rc1 { intending c4 White has some initiative, although Black seems to be ok. Anyway, there is no reason to go into this. } ) 11. Nxf3 Qc7 { [%csl Re5] Now e5 is a target. } 12. Rc1 { [%cal Gc2c4] The most critical reply. White wants to play c4 and take back with the rook. } 12... Rd8 { [%cal Gd8d1] [%cal Rc2c4] [%csl Rd1] A good prophylactic move that prevents White's plan. } 13. c3 { If } ( 13. c4 { then just } 13... dxc4 { and Black's rook is hitting White's queen. } ) 13... Ng6 { [%csl Re5] Giving White something to worry about: the e5-pawn! } 14. Bd4 Be7 { [%cal Ge8g8] Just developing. It is too risky to take the pawn. After } ( 14... Ngxe5 15. Nxe5 Nxe5 16. Bb5+ Nc6 17. Qh5 { White has a strong initiative. } ) 15. Qd2 O-O 16. Qe3 { Another way to protect e5. } 16... Nh4 $1 { [%cal Gh4f3] The simplification makes Black's life a lot easier. } 17. Nxh4 Bxh4 18. Bd3 { Improving the bishop. } ( 18. g3 Be7 { doesn't change much. } ) 18... Rc8 { [%cal Gc6d4] Intending to take on d4. } 19. Qh3 { The most threatening and the only move that has been played. Possible is } ( 19. g3 Be7 20. Rcd1 { , in order to avoid mass exchanges. Still, after } 20... Nxd4 21. cxd4 Qb6 22. Rd2 g6 { , Black has a firm position without weaknesses. } ) 19... Nxd4 { [%cal Gc8c1] [%csl Rc1] } 20. Bxh7+ { A nice idea. } ( 20. Qxh4 Nf5 21. Bxf5 exf5 { is just equal, for instance } 22. Qf4 Rce8 23. Rce1 f6 { . } ) 20... Kxh7 21. Qxh4+ Kg8 22. Qxd4 { Of course not } ( 22. cxd4 $2 Qxc1 { . } ) 22... Qa5 23. a3 Rc4 { [%cal Gf8c8] [%cal Gb7b5] White has won a pawn yet Black has excellent compensation, as shown in an email game. Black doubled rooks on the c-file and started pushing the pawns on the queenside and easily drew. } * 

