1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 { This aggressive push has become increasingly popular, and you can understand why. It is a good move. Firstly, } ( 4. h4 { contains a trap: the natural } 4... e6 { loses the bishop after } ( 4... h6 { can be met by } 5. g4 { , grabbing space. That leaves the principled answer } ) ( 4... h5 { , which gives White the g5-square. } ) 5. g4 $1 { Also, the typical Caro-Kann move } ) 4... h5 { We play it. It is the best move. We can live with the weakened g5-square. After Meanwhile, after However, Now, after } ( 4... e6 $2 5. g4 Bg6 6. h5 Be4 7. f3 { the bishop is gone. } ) ( 4... h6 5. g4 Bd7 6. h5 { White takes a lot of space. } ) ( 4... Qc7 $1 $2 { could be investigated: } 5. g4 Bd7 6. Nc3 e6 { leads to a complicated kind of French. } ) ( 4... h5 { , the two main moves for White are } 5. Bd3 { and } ( 5. c4 { . They will be covered in separate chapters. Here, I check some more rare tries. } ) ) 5. Ne2 { This looks strange, but the knight can go to g3 or f4 next. } 5... e6 6. Ng3 ( 6. Nf4 c5 $1 { gives Black the initiative. } ) 6... Bg6 7. Be2 { [%csl Gh5] Attacking the h5-pawn. } 7... c5 $1 { The typical reaction. As usual, this gives Black great play. } 8. c3 Nc6 9. Be3 { Trying to keep everything together. } 9... Qb6 { [%cal Gb6b2] Attacking b2. White will never find enough time to capture the h5-pawn. } 10. Qb3 c4 $1 11. Qxb6 axb6 12. Nd2 b5 { [%cal Gb5b4] Black is much better. Please notice that White can't prevent ...**b5-b4** with } 13. a3 { because Black plays it anyway: } 13... b4 { , possible due to the pin on the a-file. } * 

