1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 { This aggressive push has become increasingly popular, and you can understand why. It is a good move. Firstly, } ( 4. h4 { contains a trap: the natural } 4... e6 { loses the bishop after } ( 4... h6 { can be met by } 5. g4 { , grabbing space. That leaves the principled answer } ) ( 4... h5 { , which gives White the g5-square. } ) 5. g4 $1 { Also, the typical Caro-Kann move } ) 4... h5 { We play it. It is the best move. We can live with the weakened g5-square. After Meanwhile, after However, Now, after } ( 4... e6 $2 5. g4 Bg6 6. h5 Be4 7. f3 { the bishop is gone. } ) ( 4... h6 5. g4 Bd7 6. h5 { White takes a lot of space. } ) ( 4... Qc7 $1 $2 { could be investigated: } 5. g4 Bd7 6. Nc3 e6 { leads to a complicated kind of French. } ) ( 4... h5 { , the two main moves for White are } 5. Bd3 { and } ( 5. c4 { . They will be covered in separate chapters. Here, I check some more rare tries. } ) ) 5. Bg5 { Immediately exploiting the juicy g5-square. } 5... Qb6 $1 { [%csl Rb2] At once pointing at the weak spot on b2. } 6. Bd3 { White must play actively. } ( 6. b3 e6 7. Nf3 c5 { is already much better for Black. } ) 6... Qxd4 $1 { This works, so we go for it! Alternatively, the more safe continuation } ( 6... Bxd3 { could also be played. However, after } 7. Qxd3 { it leads to very double-edged play. } 7... Qxb2 { is a mistake because of } ( 7... e6 { is forced, but that leads to a position that we try to avoid. Compare with the lines after 5... h5 5.Bd3 , where we answer 5...Bxd3 6.Qxd3 Qa5+! and not 6...e6 . } ) 8. e6 $1 { and White has won a lot of nice games from here. This means that } ) 7. Nf3 { [%csl Gd4] [%csl Ge5] Not } ( 7. Bxf5 Qxe5+ { followed by ...Qxf5, winning. } ) 7... Qg4 { [%cal Gg4f5] } 8. Bxf5 { Best. After } ( 8. O-O Bxd3 9. Qxd3 e6 { White doesn't have enough for the pawn. } ) 8... Qxf5 9. c4 { This is premature. } 9... Qe4+ $1 10. Be3 e6 { Don't be too greedy. } ( 10... Qxc4 { is hit by } 11. e6 $1 fxe6 12. Nbd2 { when White gets a dangerous initiative. } ) 11. Nbd2 Qd3 { [%csl Gd3] [%csl Re1] A cool queen. } 12. Rc1 Bb4 { Preventing Rc3. White is forced to push Black's annoying queen away from d3 in some way. } 13. cxd5 exd5 14. a3 Bxd2+ 15. Bxd2 Ne7 16. Rc3 Qe4+ { Staying on the diagonal with } ( 16... Qa6 { in order to prevent White from castling runs into } 17. e6 $1 fxe6 18. Ng5 { with a strong attack. } ) 17. Re3 Qg4 { [%csl Rg2] } 18. O-O Na6 { [%cal Ge7f5] [%cal Ge8g8] [%cal Ge8c8] Black is still a pawn up with a solid position. } * 

