[Black "10) Tal Variation: 5.Bd3 with 7.b4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 { The automatic reaction. Always meet White's h4 with ...h5! } 5. Bd3 { [%cal Gd3f5] A simple and easy to understand move: White exchanges Black's strong Caro-Kann bishop. } 5... Bxd3 6. Qxd3 { Positionally Black is doing fine after the exchange of the light-squared bishops. White is counting on the extra space, the nice g5-outpost and quick development. } 6... Qa5+ $1 { [%cal Rb1d2] [%cal Rc1d2] This check has become the modern mainline. It disturbs White's natural play. The traditional move } ( 6... e6 { is playable of course, but it allows } 7. Bg5 { which I prefer to avoid. White can also just develop with } ( 7. Nf3 { , but that is less threatening. } ) ) 7. b4 $5 { A surprising pawn sacrifice. } 7... Qa6 $5 { [%cal Ga6d3] [%cal Gb8a6] Trying to keep more positional control is probably something that appeals to most Caro-Kann players. } 8. Qb3 { Keeping the queens on is a serious option, but Black's queen is good on a6 from where it prevents White from castling. } 8... e6 { [%cal Gg8e7] [%cal Ge7f5] } 9. Ne2 Ne7 10. Nd2 Nf5 { When the knight gets to f5, Black is usually doing fine. } 11. Nf3 Nd7 { The immediate } ( 11... Qc4 { , going for an ending, is also fine. } ) 12. a4 { [%cal Gb4b5] } 12... Qc4 $1 { [%cal Gc4b3] [%cal Gf8e7] Black is fine. A top game continued } 13. Bd2 Qxb3 14. cxb3 f6 15. O-O Be7 16. g3 Kf7 17. Rfe1 { Caruana-Firouzja, Grand Swiss 2021. Here Black prematurely took on e5. After a flexible move like } 17... a6 { or } ( 17... Bd8 { the position is just balanced: } ) ( 17... Bd8 $1 $2 18. Kg2 a6 19. Rac1 Bb6 { and Black is fine. } ) * 

