1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 { The automatic reaction. Always meet White's h4 with ...h5! } 5. Bd3 { [%cal Gd3f5] A simple and easy to understand move: White exchanges Black's strong Caro-Kann bishop. } 5... Bxd3 6. Qxd3 { Positionally Black is doing fine after the exchange of the light-squared bishops. White is counting on the extra space, the nice g5-outpost and quick development. } 6... Qa5+ $1 { [%cal Rb1d2] [%cal Rc1d2] This check has become the modern mainline. It disturbs White's natural play. The traditional move } ( 6... e6 { is playable of course, but it allows } 7. Bg5 { which I prefer to avoid. White can also just develop with } ( 7. Nf3 { , but that is less threatening. } ) ) 7. b4 $5 { A surprising pawn sacrifice. } 7... Qa6 $5 { [%cal Ga6d3] [%cal Gb8a6] Trying to keep more positional control is probably something that appeals to most Caro-Kann players. } 8. Qb3 { Keeping the queens on is a serious option, but Black's queen is good on a6 from where it prevents White from castling. } 8... e6 { [%cal Gg8e7] [%cal Ge7f5] } 9. Nf3 Qc4 $1 { [%cal Gc4b3] Black is fine in the ending. } ( 9... Ne7 10. a4 Nf5 11. Bd2 Nd7 12. Nc3 { gave White the initiative in Firouzja-Erigaisi, blitz 2024. } ) 10. Bd2 { After } ( 10. Qxc4 dxc4 { Black has a nice square on d5. } ) 10... Ne7 11. Na3 { Forcing us to take. } 11... Qxb3 12. axb3 f6 { [%cal Gf6e5] [%cal Ge7g6] [%cal Gb8d7] [%csl Re5] Black has good counterplay and can gradually finish development. A sample line goes } 13. O-O Ng6 14. c4 Be7 15. g3 Kf7 16. Nc2 Nd7 17. Rfe1 a6 { , with a balanced game. Black can play ...Nb6 and put pressure on c4. } * 

