1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 { The automatic reaction. Always meet White's h4 with ...h5! } 5. Bd3 { [%cal Gd3f5] A simple and easy to understand move: White exchanges Black's strong Caro-Kann bishop. } 5... Bxd3 6. Qxd3 { Positionally Black is doing fine after the exchange of the light-squared bishops. White is counting on the extra space, the nice g5-outpost and quick development. } 6... Qa5+ $1 { [%cal Rb1d2] [%cal Rc1d2] This check has become the modern mainline. It disturbs White's natural play. The traditional move } ( 6... e6 { is playable of course, but it allows } 7. Bg5 { which I prefer to avoid. White can also just develop with } ( 7. Nf3 { , but that is less threatening. } ) ) 7. b4 $5 { A surprising pawn sacrifice. } 7... Qa6 $5 { [%cal Ga6d3] [%cal Gb8a6] Trying to keep more positional control is probably something that appeals to most Caro-Kann players. } 8. e6 { A spectacular move that has scored really well. Black should be fine, though, after some precise play. } 8... Qxd3 9. cxd3 { White has scored well from this position, but Black is absolutely ok. } 9... fxe6 10. Nd2 Nh6 { [%cal Gh6f5] } 11. Ndf3 { This is the right knight. The other should go to f4. } 11... Nf5 12. Nh3 { [%csl Ge5] [%csl Gf4] [%csl Gg5] White controls e5, f4 and g5, so it looks quite dangerous. An appropiate return of the pawn solves all development issues for Black. } 12... g6 13. Nf4 a5 $1 { [%cal Ga8a2] [%csl Rb4] Creating counterplay. } 14. Nxe6 { Worse is } ( 14. Nxg6 Rg8 { . } ) 14... Kd7 15. Nxf8+ ( 15. Nc5+ Kc8 { is also fine for Black. } ) 15... Rxf8 16. bxa5 Rxa5 { [%cal Ga5a4] [%csl Rd4] [%csl Gf5] The position is still kind of balanced, but I like the knight on f5. From here Black won a nice game in Bersamina- Bluebaum (See "Bersamina- Bluebaum" variation from the PGN), Budapest 2024, which you can find in the Model Games. } * 

