1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 { The automatic reaction. Always meet White's h4 with ...h5! } 5. Bd3 { [%cal Gd3f5] A simple and easy to understand move: White exchanges Black's strong Caro-Kann bishop. } 5... Bxd3 6. Qxd3 { Positionally Black is doing fine after the exchange of the light-squared bishops. White is counting on the extra space, the nice g5-outpost and quick development. } 6... Qa5+ $1 { [%cal Rb1d2] [%cal Rc1d2] This check has become the modern mainline. It disturbs White's natural play. The traditional move } ( 6... e6 { is playable of course, but it allows } 7. Bg5 { which I prefer to avoid. White can also just develop with } ( 7. Nf3 { , but that is less threatening. } ) ) 7. b4 $5 { A surprising pawn sacrifice. } 7... Qxb4+ { Accepting the pawn is maybe best, theoretically speaking, but White gets a lot of possibilities and at least a long-term initiative. } 8. Nd2 e6 9. Rb1 { [%csl Rb4] [%csl Rb7] } 9... Qe7 { [%cal Ge7b7] Black should be able to defend. The position is closed, so we should be able to handle White's better development. The engines call it balanced, which is probably a correct evaluation. Personally, I like having an extra pawn... } 10. Ne2 b5 $1 { [%csl Gc4] Black prevents White's c4 for good. } 11. a4 { White must challenge Black's structure. } ( 11. Nf3 { can be met by } 11... a5 { or } ( 11... Qc7 { . } ) ) 11... b4 { An active response. The solid } ( 11... a6 { has been played in most games, and is also fine. } ) 12. c3 { Or } ( 12. Nb3 a5 { , with the usual complications. } ) 12... Qb7 { [%cal Gf8b4] [%csl Gb4] Black can also go } ( 12... a5 { . } ) 13. O-O { White can't exploit the pin on the b-file. } ( 13. cxb4 Bxb4 14. O-O Ne7 { is fine for Black because } 15. a5 { , trying to use the pin of the bishop, is met by } 15... Qa6 $1 16. Qf3 c5 { and Black is much better. } ) 13... Qa6 $1 { [%cal Ga6e2] [%csl Rd3] [%csl Re2] } 14. Qf3 { In Diaz Mino-Domingo Nunez, 2025 White played } ( 14. c4 { , which Black could have met by } 14... Nh6 { followed by ...Nf5 with a good position. } ) 14... bxc3 15. Qxc3 { White could and possible should try this move. } 15... Qxe2 { Black can keep the game going with } ( 15... Nd7 $1 $2 { . } ) 16. Rxb8+ { [%cal Gc3c6] } 16... Rxb8 17. Qxc6+ Kd8 18. Nb3 $1 { White has enough compensation to draw. } 18... Rxb3 { The line continues } 19. Qa8+ Kd7 20. Qxa7+ Kc8 21. Bg5 Qc2 22. Rc1 Rb1 { and White has to settle for a repetition with } 23. Qa8+ Kc7 24. Qa7+ Kc8 { . } * 

