1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bd3 Bxd3 6. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 7. c3 { A solid move. The downside is that White's position loses a lot of its flexibility. } 7... e6 8. Nf3 Qa6 $1 { [%cal Ga6d3] One of the points of **6...Qa5+**. } 9. Qxa6 ( 9. Qc2 c5 { is good for Black. Let's check the queen exchange instead. } ) 9... Nxa6 { [%cal Gg8e7] [%cal Ge7f5] [%csl Rc1] [%csl Gf5] Objectively, the ending is probably balanced, but I like Black. We have a nice square on f5 for a knight and a lot of White's pawns are fixed on dark squares, making our bishop the good one and theirs the potentially really bad one. A sample line goes } 10. O-O Ne7 11. b4 Nf5 12. a4 Nc7 { and Black is soon ready to strike on the queenside with ...a7-a5. If White plays } 13. a5 { then another pawn is on a dark square, and Black can still open up the position with ...b6 at an appropiate moment, maybe start with } 13... Be7 { and if } 14. Bg5 f6 15. Bf4 Nb5 { followed by ...Kd7 with a complicated ending that is objectively balanced, but full of play. } * 

