1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bd3 Bxd3 6. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 7. c3 { A solid move. The downside is that White's position loses a lot of its flexibility. } 7... e6 8. a4 { Expanding on the queenside is the most popular idea. } 8... c5 ( 8... Qa6 { is possible, but after } 9. Qd1 c5 10. Na3 { we see the point of **8.a4** : the knight is coming to b5 with big threats. That said, it it absolutely playable for Black after } 10... cxd4 11. Nb5 Qb6 { , for example } 12. Nxd4 Nc6 13. Ngf3 { as in the game Blomqvist-Mitrabha, 2024, and now the precise } 13... Bc5 $1 { Ν with a balanced game. } ) 9. dxc5 { Black can't take back with the bishop. } 9... Qxc5 10. Nf3 Qc7 { [%cal Gb8c6] Regrouping with a fine position. Next comes ...Nc6. } 11. Na3 a6 { [%cal Gb8c6] [%cal Gg8e7] [%cal Ge7f5] [%csl Rb5] To stop Nb5. Black is fine. } ( 11... Bxa3 $1 $2 12. Rxa3 Nd7 13. O-O Ne7 14. Re1 { was somewhat better for White in Rapport-Carlsen, Germany 2024. } ) * 

