1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bd3 Bxd3 6. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 7. Bd2 { [%csl Ra5] This gains a tempo on the annoying black queen. } 7... Qa6 { [%cal Ga6d3] One of the key ideas of **6...Qa5+**. Black would love to get the queens off. } 8. e6 $5 { An inspired try. } ( 8. Qxa6 Nxa6 9. Nf3 e6 { is fine for Black. White's extra space doesn't matter with so few pieces left on the board, and Black has nice breaks with ...c5 and ...f6. Furthermore, White's bishop could be really bad in the ending with pawns on d4, e5 and h4. } ) 8... Qxd3 9. cxd3 fxe6 10. Nf3 { This is a genuine pawn sacrifice. White gets good compensation with nice squares on e5, f4 and g5, but if Black concentrates on development and just returns the pawn there are no problems whatsoever. } 10... Nd7 { [%cal Gg8h6] [%cal Gh6f5] } 11. O-O Nh6 { Black doesn't intend to protect the e6-pawn. } 12. Re1 Nf5 13. Rxe6 Kf7 { [%csl Re6] Kicking the rook away. } 14. Re2 { If } ( 14. Ng5+ Kg8 { White's knight has to return to f3 in order to protect d4 and h4. } 15. Nf3 Kf7 { is a repetition. } ) 14... e6 $1 { [%cal Gf8e7] [%cal Gf8d6] A novelty from my book. Only } ( 14... g6 { has been played previously. } ) 15. Ng5+ Kg8 16. Nxe6 Bd6 $5 { [%cal Gf5h4] [%csl Rh4] The most precise. White is better coordinated after } ( 16... Nxh4 17. Bg5 Nf5 18. Nd2 Bd6 19. Nf3 { , although objectively it is still equal. } ) 17. g3 { Or } ( 17. Na3 Nxh4 { , regaining the pawn with a good position. } ) 17... Nf8 { [%cal Gf8e6] [%cal Gg8f7] Now after } 18. Bc3 { White hangs on to the d4-pawn, but it is ugly. Black has excellent compensation. A sample line goes } ( 18. Bc3 Nxe6 19. Rxe6 Kf7 20. Re2 b5 21. b3 b4 22. Bb2 Rhe8 23. Kf1 Bxg3 $1 24. Rxe8 Rxe8 25. fxg3 Ne3+ $1 26. Kg1 Nc2 27. Kf2 Rb8 $1 28. Nd2 Nxa1 29. Bxa1 Rb6 { followed by ...Ra6 and wins. } ) * 

