1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bd3 Bxd3 6. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 7. Bd2 { [%csl Ra5] This gains a tempo on the annoying black queen. } 7... Qa6 { [%cal Ga6d3] One of the key ideas of **6...Qa5+**. Black would love to get the queens off. } 8. e6 $5 { An inspired try. } ( 8. Qxa6 Nxa6 9. Nf3 e6 { is fine for Black. White's extra space doesn't matter with so few pieces left on the board, and Black has nice breaks with ...c5 and ...f6. Furthermore, White's bishop could be really bad in the ending with pawns on d4, e5 and h4. } ) 8... Qxd3 9. exf7+ Kxf7 10. cxd3 Nd7 { [%cal Gg8h6] [%cal Gh6f5] } 11. Nf3 Nh6 { Black uses all the available squares. We are not afraid of Bxh6 - we'd just take back with the rook when it is active! If White doesn't take then the knight can go to f5, but we also want to fianchetto our bishop and from h6 the knight is not blocking the bishop's job. } 12. Bc3 { A solid setup. } 12... e6 { [%cal Gf8d6] [%cal Gf8e7] } 13. Nbd2 Re8 { Protecting the e-pawn. } ( 13... Be7 { allows } 14. Ng5+ { , which is awkward. } ) 14. O-O Nf5 15. g3 Be7 16. Rfe1 Bf6 { [%cal Ge8e7] [%cal Gh8e8] [%cal Gb7b6] [%cal Gc6c5] The position is balanced. It is a strategic endgame in which I like Black's long-term potential based on the better pawn structure and a stronger bishop. } * 

