1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bd3 Bxd3 6. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 7. Nc3 { Quick development. On the downside, this means that White can't protect the d4-pawn with c2-c3. } 7... e6 { [%cal Gc6c5] } 8. Ne2 c5 $5 { The most direct. } ( 8... Qa6 { is the most played move, but when White's knight already is on e2 there is no need to include it so early. Developing with } ) ( 8... Ne7 { is also fine. } ) 9. Bd2 { [%cal Gc3b5] Introducing **Nb5** ideas. } ( 9. dxc5 Bxc5 { is no problem. } ) 9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 { If } ( 10. Nb5 { we reply } 10... Qb6 { . } ) 10... Nc6 11. Ncb5 { [%cal Gd2a5] } ( 11. Nxc6 bxc6 { is good for Black. } ) 11... Qb6 12. a4 { Trying to kick Black's queen back. After } ( 12. Be3 { Black can probably get away with } 12... Nxe5 { , but } ( 12... Qa5+ { is a simpler answer. White doesn't have anything better than repeating with } 13. Bd2 Qb6 { . } ) ) 12... a6 { [%csl Rb5] } 13. a5 Qd8 14. Nxc6 bxc6 15. Qc3 $5 { [%cal Gc3c6] A tricky move. } 15... Rc8 { Just protecting c6. Don't take: } ( 15... cxb5 $2 16. Qc6+ Ke7 17. Bb4+ { and it is game over. } ) 16. Nd6+ Bxd6 17. exd6 Nf6 { [%cal Ge8g8] [%csl Rd6] The g7-pawn was hanging. The position is pretty unclear, but Black will castle next and in the long run the d6-pawn will probably fall. } * 

