1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bd3 Bxd3 6. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 7. Nd2 { [%cal Ya5a6] [%cal Yc2c4] This is clearly the most played move and one of the most important modern Caro-Kann lines. } 7... e6 8. Nf3 Nh6 { [%cal Gh6f5] [%csl Gf5] The modern response. The knight is heading for the excellent f5-square. } ( 8... Qa6 { is popular, and I have played it myself. White responds with } 9. c4 { and now Black can continue development with } 9... Bb4 { or } ( 9... Nh6 { . This is playable, of course, but these days I prefer to start by improving the kingside instead of provoking the move c2-c4, which is a move White would like to play anyway. Play might continue } ) ( 9... Bb4 10. O-O Ne7 { followed by ...c5 with an interesting game. } ) ) 9. O-O Nf5 { A very important position arises. Here White has tried different ideas. } 10. Nb3 { [%csl Ra5] The human choice. } 10... Qa6 { [%cal Ga6d3] The most natural reply. } ( 10... Qb5 { is also possible. Black doesn't have to fear the ending despite the doubled pawns, and after the universaly played } 11. Qd1 { Black gets the important } 11... c5 { break in. This has been played more than 100 times and seems ok for Black. I prefer **10...Qa6** , though. } ) 11. Qc3 { This move is designed to make the freeing break ...c5 harder to achieve. } 11... Qb6 { Improving the queen and making room for the a-pawn. } 12. Bg5 a5 { [%cal Ga5a4] } 13. a4 { Otherwise Black plays ...a4. } 13... Nd7 { [%cal Gc6c5] Black is ready to play ...**c5** , which solves all problems. A recent game continued } 14. Qd3 c5 15. c4 dxc4 16. Qxc4 { Van Batenburg-Korchynskyi, Holland 2025. Here } 16... Nxd4 $1 17. Nfxd4 cxd4 18. Rfe1 Qb4 { leads to equal play. } * 

