1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bd3 Bxd3 6. Qxd3 Qa5+ $1 7. Nd2 { [%cal Ya5a6] [%cal Yc2c4] This is clearly the most played move and one of the most important modern Caro-Kann lines. } 7... e6 8. Nf3 Nh6 { [%cal Gh6f5] [%csl Gf5] The modern response. The knight is heading for the excellent f5-square. } ( 8... Qa6 { is popular, and I have played it myself. White responds with } 9. c4 { and now Black can continue development with } 9... Bb4 { or } ( 9... Nh6 { . This is playable, of course, but these days I prefer to start by improving the kingside instead of provoking the move c2-c4, which is a move White would like to play anyway. Play might continue } ) ( 9... Bb4 10. O-O Ne7 { followed by ...c5 with an interesting game. } ) ) 9. O-O Nf5 { A very important position arises. Here White has tried different ideas. } 10. c4 { In principle this is a natural strike, but White is not ready to make this move. } 10... Be7 { [%csl Rh4] Hitting h4. } 11. g3 O-O { Black has saved a move by refraining from ...Qa6. } 12. b3 { Preparing Bb2. } ( 12. a3 Qa6 { pins the c-pawn, and after } 13. Qc2 Nd7 { Black is fine. } ) 12... Rd8 $1 { [%cal Gc6c5] A strong preparatory move. Black will strike with ...c5 next. } 13. Bb2 { After } ( 13. a4 c5 $1 { Black is doing great. } ) 13... c5 $1 { This is simply good for Black. White has a miserable score from this position. Nothing really works. } 14. Qe2 { Getting away from Black's rook. } 14... cxd4 15. Nxd4 Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Nc6 { [%cal Gc6d4] [%csl Rd4] With tempo. } 17. Bb2 d4 $1 { [%cal Gd4d3] [%cal Gc6e5] [%cal Ga5e5] The point of the simplifications. } 18. Nf3 { To protect e5. } 18... d3 $1 { The d-pawn is strong. } 19. Qe4 Rd7 20. Rfd1 Rad8 { Black is better. A sample line goes } 21. a3 d2 $1 { Eventually this pawn will be lost, but there will be other gains. } 22. Qc2 Rd3 23. Kg2 Qc7 24. Rxd2 Rxd2 25. Nxd2 Nxe5 { and Black regains the pawn with a good position. } * 

