1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. c4 { This is also quite a popular move. } ( 5. c4 { looks aggressive, but it is also a good positional move: White will play Nc3 next and hopes to enjoy active pieces and a lot of extra space. } ) 5... e6 6. Nc3 dxc4 $1 { [%csl Gd5] An important strategic decision. Black changes the structure to get a nice square on d5. The most played continuation is } ( 6... Ne7 7. Nge2 Nd7 { , but White has the initiative after } 8. Ng3 Bg6 9. Bg5 Qb6 10. Rc1 $1 { . Maybe Black can get away with } 10... Qxb2 { , but it looks dangerous after } ( 10... Qxb2 { , the World Champion tried } ) ( 10... f6 11. exf6 gxf6 12. Be3 Qxb2 { , but after } 13. cxd5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. Bd3 { White had good play, Gurel-Gukesh, Grand Swiss 2025. } ) 11. Bd3 { with good play for the pawn. Instead of } ) 7. Bxc4 Nd7 8. Bg5 Be7 { [%csl Rg5] This seems to be the simplest. } 9. Qd2 { If } ( 9. Nf3 { then } 9... Bg4 $1 { is good. We will see this same idea in the next trainable - 8... Nd7 8.Nf3 Bg4! } ) 9... Qb6 10. Nge2 O-O-O { [%cal Gd7e5] Black has good play. The threat ...Nxe5 is already a bit annoying for White. } * 

