1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. c4 { This is also quite a popular move. } ( 5. c4 { looks aggressive, but it is also a good positional move: White will play Nc3 next and hopes to enjoy active pieces and a lot of extra space. } ) 5... e6 6. Nc3 dxc4 $1 { [%csl Gd5] An important strategic decision. Black changes the structure to get a nice square on d5. The most played continuation is } ( 6... Ne7 7. Nge2 Nd7 { , but White has the initiative after } 8. Ng3 Bg6 9. Bg5 Qb6 10. Rc1 $1 { . Maybe Black can get away with } 10... Qxb2 { , but it looks dangerous after } ( 10... Qxb2 { , the World Champion tried } ) ( 10... f6 11. exf6 gxf6 12. Be3 Qxb2 { , but after } 13. cxd5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. Bd3 { White had good play, Gurel-Gukesh, Grand Swiss 2025. } ) 11. Bd3 { with good play for the pawn. Instead of } ) 7. Bxc4 Nd7 8. Be2 { [%csl Rh5] Hitting h5. } 8... Ne7 $1 { Just ignoring it. } 9. Bxh5 c5 $1 { [%csl Rd4] Black takes the initiative with this well-timed break while White is uncoordinated. } 10. Bf3 { This was Gevorgyan-Petrosian, 2019. } 10... Qb6 $1 { [%cal Ge8c8] [%cal Gc5d4] [%cal Gd7e5] In the mentioned game Black took on **d4** , which was fine. } ( 10... Qb6 { is probably even stronger, though. } ) 11. Nge2 Nc6 { [%csl Rd4] [%csl Re5] With a strong initiative. A sample line goes } 12. Bxc6 Qxc6 13. d5 exd5 14. Qxd5 Qxd5 15. Nxd5 O-O-O $1 { Now e5 hangs and the d5-knight is insecure. } 16. Ne3 Bd3 17. f4 c4 { Black can increase the pressure with ...Nc5 or break with ...f6. } * 

