1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. c4 { This is also quite a popular move. } ( 5. c4 { looks aggressive, but it is also a good positional move: White will play Nc3 next and hopes to enjoy active pieces and a lot of extra space. } ) 5... e6 6. Nc3 dxc4 $1 { [%csl Gd5] An important strategic decision. Black changes the structure to get a nice square on d5. The most played continuation is } ( 6... Ne7 7. Nge2 Nd7 { , but White has the initiative after } 8. Ng3 Bg6 9. Bg5 Qb6 10. Rc1 $1 { . Maybe Black can get away with } 10... Qxb2 { , but it looks dangerous after } ( 10... Qxb2 { , the World Champion tried } ) ( 10... f6 11. exf6 gxf6 12. Be3 Qxb2 { , but after } 13. cxd5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. Bd3 { White had good play, Gurel-Gukesh, Grand Swiss 2025. } ) 11. Bd3 { with good play for the pawn. Instead of } ) 7. Bxc4 Nd7 8. Bb3 { A new move that has been tried by some strong players the last couple of years. } 8... Be7 9. Bc2 { [%cal Gc2f5] Exchanging the bishops. This is White's idea. On } ( 9. g3 { , the reply } 9... Qb6 { followed by ...O-O-O looks good. } ) 9... Bxc2 10. Qxc2 Bxh4 { Taking the pawn is very concrete. Also worth considering is } ( 10... c5 { , defending actively. } ) 11. Nf3 { [%csl Rh4] } ( 11. Ne4 Be7 { transposes. } ) 11... Be7 12. Ne4 { White has compensation, but no more than that. } 12... Nb6 13. Bg5 f6 $1 { [%csl Rg5] This is forced. Otherwise we can't protect the dark squares. } 14. Bd2 f5 { The most active reply. } ( 14... Qd7 { is also ok. } ) 15. Nc5 { After } ( 15. Neg5 Qd7 16. O-O-O Nd5 { Black is solid and a pawn up. } ) 15... Bxc5 16. dxc5 Nd5 { [%cal Gd8c7] [%cal Gd8d7] [%cal Ge8c8] The engine calls it a balanced position. I like our extra pawn, though. Black's structure is firm, so it is difficult for White to create any real threats. } * 

