1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. c4 { This line should be compared with the line } ( 4. h4 h5 5. c4 { . Basically, White strategy is the same: to develop very actively. } ) 4... e6 { [%cal Gf8b4] [%cal Gg8e7] [%cal Gd5c4] Because nothing has happened on the kingside yet, Black doesn't need to look out for any Bg5-stuff and has some interesting extra options. } 5. Nc3 Bb4 $5 { This is one of Black's extra possibilities. Often Black plays } ( 5... Ne7 { or even } ) ( 5... dxc4 { , but I like this } ) ( 5... Bb4 { plan very much. It leads to an interesting positional struggle where Black is doing great. } ) 6. cxd5 cxd5 { Here } ( 6... Qxd5 { is met by } 7. Ne2 { . } ) 7. h4 $5 { [%cal Gh4h5] [%cal Gg2g4] [%csl Rf5] This is modern chess. White grabs space on the kingside. Otherwise Black is just fine with a sound position. } 7... h6 { [%cal Gf5h7] Saving the bishop. } 8. g4 Bh7 $1 { [%cal Gh6h5] It is best to go to h7 in one go. } ( 8... Be4 9. f3 Bh7 10. h5 Nc6 11. Bd3 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Qb6 13. Ne2 { is pleasant for White with their extra space. } ) 9. h5 { The move-order matters! } ( 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 h5 $1 { ruins White's dream of control. } ) 9... Nc6 10. Bd3 Be4 $5 { [%csl Rh1] A sharp move. We want to avoid } ( 10... Bxd3 11. Qxd3 { , but maybe 11...Bxc3+Ν 12.bxc3 } 11... Qd7 { is still ok for Black. } ) 11. f3 Qa5 $1 { [%cal Gb4c3] [%csl Rc3] This is the important tactic that makes the **10...Be4** idea playable. } 12. fxe4 Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 Qxc3+ { [%csl Ra1] [%csl Rd3] [%csl Re1] } 14. Qd2 Qxa1 { [%cal Gc6d4] [%cal Gg8e7] [%cal Ge8c8] [%cal Ge8g8] [%csl Rd4] The complications work for Black. A sample line goes } 15. exd5 Nxd4 16. Qb2 Qxb2 17. Bxb2 Rd8 $1 18. Bxd4 Rxd5 19. Nf3 Ne7 20. Bc4 Ra5 21. Bb3 O-O { with a complicated ending with chances for both sides. The engine calls it 0.00, but I think it is easier to play as Black. Next comes ...Nc6. } * 

