1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. c4 { This line should be compared with the line } ( 4. h4 h5 5. c4 { . Basically, White strategy is the same: to develop very actively. } ) 4... e6 { [%cal Gf8b4] [%cal Gg8e7] [%cal Gd5c4] Because nothing has happened on the kingside yet, Black doesn't need to look out for any Bg5-stuff and has some interesting extra options. } 5. Nc3 Bb4 $5 { This is one of Black's extra possibilities. Often Black plays } ( 5... Ne7 { or even } ) ( 5... dxc4 { , but I like this } ) ( 5... Bb4 { plan very much. It leads to an interesting positional struggle where Black is doing great. } ) 6. Nf3 { [%csl Rf3] Just developing, but often f3 is not the optimal square for the knight in these c4-systems. } 6... Ne7 { [%cal Ge8g8] [%cal Gc6c5] [%cal Gd5c4] } 7. Be2 { White continues to get their pieces out. The position after } ( 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 { is covered via the move order (See "the move order" variation from the PGN) **6.a3** , and } ) ( 7. Qb3 a5 { leads to the line (See "the line" variation from the PGN) **6.Qb3**. } ) 7... dxc4 { [%cal Re2c4] [%csl Re2] This capture now makes a lot of sense, since White has moved the bishop and is forced to move it again. } 8. Bxc4 c5 { [%csl Rd1] This typical strike comes at a really uncomfortable moment for White. They have no control over the d5-square and taking on c5 would lose the right to castle. } 9. dxc5 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 { Black is just better regardless, but it can be hard to decide what to play next! } 10... O-O { [%cal Gb8d7] [%cal Gf5g4] [%csl Rc5] [%csl Re5] } 11. Nb5 Nd7 12. Nd6 Bg4 $1 { [%cal Ge7c6] [%cal Gd7c5] [%cal Gd7e5] [%cal Gc6e5] Black has the initiative. A sample line goes } 13. Nxb7 Rab8 14. a3 Rxb7 15. axb4 Rxb4 16. Rxa7 Nxc5 17. Rxe7 Rxc4 18. Be3 Rd8+ 19. Ke1 Rc2 { and White will never survive, despite the reduced material. } * 

