1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. c4 { This line should be compared with the line } ( 4. h4 h5 5. c4 { . Basically, White strategy is the same: to develop very actively. } ) 4... e6 { [%cal Gf8b4] [%cal Gg8e7] [%cal Gd5c4] Because nothing has happened on the kingside yet, Black doesn't need to look out for any Bg5-stuff and has some interesting extra options. } 5. Nc3 Bb4 $5 { This is one of Black's extra possibilities. Often Black plays } ( 5... Ne7 { or even } ) ( 5... dxc4 { , but I like this } ) ( 5... Bb4 { plan very much. It leads to an interesting positional struggle where Black is doing great. } ) 6. a3 { [%csl Rb4] } 6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Ne7 { An interesting strategic position. White has the bishop pair, but Black is doing well on the light squares, helped by the strong Caro-Kann bishop on f5. } 8. a4 { [%cal Gc1a3] Intending Ba3. This idea is often seen in the French. } 8... c5 { [%cal Gb8c6] [%cal Gc5d4] } 9. Nf3 Nbc6 10. Ba3 Qa5 { [%cal Gc5d4] [%csl Rc3] Black's counterplay just flows. } 11. Qd2 cxd4 12. cxd4 Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2 Na5 $1 { [%cal Ga5b3] [%cal Ga5c4] [%csl Rc4] Attacking c4 and threatening ...Nb3+. Black was much better and won quickly in Vishnu-Aronyak, India 2023. } * 

