1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. c4 { This line should be compared with the line } ( 4. h4 h5 5. c4 { . Basically, White strategy is the same: to develop very actively. } ) 4... e6 { [%cal Gf8b4] [%cal Gg8e7] [%cal Gd5c4] Because nothing has happened on the kingside yet, Black doesn't need to look out for any Bg5-stuff and has some interesting extra options. } 5. Nc3 Bb4 $5 { This is one of Black's extra possibilities. Often Black plays } ( 5... Ne7 { or even } ) ( 5... dxc4 { , but I like this } ) ( 5... Bb4 { plan very much. It leads to an interesting positional struggle where Black is doing great. } ) 6. a3 { [%csl Rb4] } 6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Ne7 { An interesting strategic position. White has the bishop pair, but Black is doing well on the light squares, helped by the strong Caro-Kann bishop on f5. } 8. Nf3 c5 $1 { [%cal Gb8c6] It is much more common just to castle, which is also fine, but why not strike in the centre immediately? } 9. Bg5 { Activating the bishop. After } ( 9. cxd5 Qxd5 { Black's queen joins the party with good play. } ) 9... Nbc6 10. Bxe7 { Not forced, but it is hard to come up with improving moves. } ( 10. Be2 dxc4 11. Bxc4 O-O 12. O-O h6 { is also good for Black. } ) 10... Nxe7 { [%cal Ge8g8] [%cal Ge7d5] [%cal Ge7c6] [%cal Gd8a5] Black is slightly better. A sample line goes } 11. Bd3 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 cxd4 13. cxd4 dxc4 14. Qxc4 O-O 15. O-O Rc8 { and the d5-square combined with the open c-file and the 2 vs 1 pawn majority on the queenside give Black a clear advantage. } * 

