1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. c4 { This line should be compared with the line } ( 4. h4 h5 5. c4 { . Basically, White strategy is the same: to develop very actively. } ) 4... e6 { [%cal Gf8b4] [%cal Gg8e7] [%cal Gd5c4] Because nothing has happened on the kingside yet, Black doesn't need to look out for any Bg5-stuff and has some interesting extra options. } 5. Nc3 Bb4 $5 { This is one of Black's extra possibilities. Often Black plays } ( 5... Ne7 { or even } ) ( 5... dxc4 { , but I like this } ) ( 5... Bb4 { plan very much. It leads to an interesting positional struggle where Black is doing great. } ) 6. Qb3 { [%csl Rb4] The most played move, attacking Black's bishop and hoping for some clarity. } 6... a5 { [%csl Gb4] A cool idea. Maybe White has something after } ( 6... Qa5 7. Nf3 Ne7 8. Bd2 h6 9. a3 Bxc3 10. Bxc3 Qb6 11. Qd1 { . } ) 7. cxd5 Qxd5 $1 { [%cal Gd5b3] This is fine for Black. } 8. Qxb4 { After } ( 8. Qxd5 exd5 { Black keeps the bishop. } ) 8... axb4 9. Nxd5 exd5 $5 { The most ambitious. } ( 9... cxd5 10. Bd2 Nc6 11. Bb5 b3 12. a4 Ne7 { was fine for Black in Kogan-Shimanov, Andorra 2024. } ) 10. Bd2 { [%cal Gd2b4] [%csl Rb4] } 10... b3 { [%csl Ra1] [%csl Ra2] } 11. a4 Ne7 { [%cal Gf5c2] [%csl Gb3] This is a pretty unclear ending. Black can protect the **b3** -pawn with ...**Bc2**. A sample line goes } 12. Nf3 b6 { Intending ...c5 in some lines. } 13. Ra3 O-O 14. Be2 Bc2 15. Bd1 c5 $1 16. Bxc2 bxc2 17. Ke2 Nbc6 18. dxc5 bxc5 19. Kd3 { The c2-pawn is gone, but Black gets fine play in several ways. I like } 19... Nc8 20. Kxc2 Nb6 21. b3 Nd7 22. Re1 Rfe8 23. Bf4 Nb4+ 24. Kd2 h6 25. h4 Nf8 { followed by ...Ne6, with tricky counterplay. } * 

