1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 { Positionally speaking, the knight is misplaced here, blocking the c-pawn. There is cunning idea behind } ( 4. Nc3 { , though. } ) 4... e6 5. g4 { The Shirov variation. White goes all-in on sharp play, trying to get the initiative with very aggressive moves. Black's structure is very firm and not so easy to overrun and modern engines confirm that this is a risky strategy for White. } 5... Bg6 6. Nge2 { [%cal Gh2h4] [%cal Ge2f4] [%csl Rg6] White wants to continue with **h4**. It is necessary to prepare this with } ( 6. Nge2 { , as the premature } ) ( 6. h4 { is met with } 6... h5 $1 { , when closing the kingside with } 7. g5 { gives Black a free hand on the other side: } 7... c5 { and Black already has good play. } ) 6... c5 { The typical break. } 7. Be3 { [%cal Ge3d4] [%cal Ge2d4] [%csl Gd4] Adding power to the centre. } 7... h5 $5 { [%cal Gh5g4] [%csl Rg4] A strong dynamic response. I recommend meeting fire with fire. We don't back down in this chapter! } 8. Nf4 { Bad for White is } ( 8. dxc5 hxg4 { . } ) 8... Bh7 { Sacrificing the h-pawn. } 9. Nxh5 Nc6 { [%csl Rd4] } 10. Bb5 { White tries to hold the d4-pawn. } 10... Ne7 $1 { [%cal Ge7c6] Flexible. Now Bxc6+ can always be met by ...Nxc6. } 11. dxc5 { The only move that has been played. } ( 11. Qd2 a6 { is good for Black. } ) 11... a6 12. Bxc6+ Nxc6 { [%cal Gc6e5] [%cal Gd5d4] [%csl Re5] } 13. Bd4 { White desperately tries to hang on to their centre. } 13... Rc8 { [%cal Gc6d4] [%cal Gf8c5] The move I recommend. The idea is just to take on d4 and play ...Bxc5 with a great game. } * 

