1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 { Positionally speaking, the knight is misplaced here, blocking the c-pawn. There is cunning idea behind } ( 4. Nc3 { , though. } ) 4... e6 5. g4 { The Shirov variation. White goes all-in on sharp play, trying to get the initiative with very aggressive moves. Black's structure is very firm and not so easy to overrun and modern engines confirm that this is a risky strategy for White. } 5... Bg6 6. Nge2 { [%cal Gh2h4] [%cal Ge2f4] [%csl Rg6] White wants to continue with **h4**. It is necessary to prepare this with } ( 6. Nge2 { , as the premature } ) ( 6. h4 { is met with } 6... h5 $1 { , when closing the kingside with } 7. g5 { gives Black a free hand on the other side: } 7... c5 { and Black already has good play. } ) 6... c5 { The typical break. } 7. Be3 { [%cal Ge3d4] [%cal Ge2d4] [%csl Gd4] Adding power to the centre. } 7... h5 $5 { [%cal Gh5g4] [%csl Rg4] A strong dynamic response. I recommend meeting fire with fire. We don't back down in this chapter! } 8. Nf4 { Bad for White is } ( 8. dxc5 hxg4 { . } ) 8... Bh7 { Sacrificing the h-pawn. } 9. dxc5 ( 9. Bb5+ Nc6 { only helps Black. } ) 9... Nc6 { [%cal Gd5d4] [%csl Rc3] [%csl Re3] Black threatens ...d4, winning a piece. White can't keep a sound structure. } 10. Qe2 { Intending to meet ...d4 with long castling, but this gives us the time to take on g4. } 10... hxg4 11. O-O-O Qa5 { [%cal Ge8c8] [%cal Gh7f5] Black already has great play. } 12. Nfxd5 { This sacrifice is the best try to stay in the game. } ( 12. Qxg4 Bf5 13. Qf3 g6 { is positionally terrible for White. } ) 12... exd5 13. Qxg4 Nge7 { [%cal Gh7f5] } 14. Nb5 { [%cal Gb5d6] White needs to come up with some threats, otherwise they are just lost. } 14... Ng6 15. Rxd5 Ngxe5 { [%cal Gf7f6] Next Black will play ...**f6** with a safe position. An email game went } 16. Qg5 f6 17. Qh5+ Ke7 18. Nc3 Be4 $1 19. Qxh8 Bxh1 20. Rd6 Kf7 { and Black was better. } * 

