1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 { Positionally speaking, the knight is misplaced here, blocking the c-pawn. There is cunning idea behind } ( 4. Nc3 { , though. } ) 4... e6 5. g4 { The Shirov variation. White goes all-in on sharp play, trying to get the initiative with very aggressive moves. Black's structure is very firm and not so easy to overrun and modern engines confirm that this is a risky strategy for White. } 5... Bg6 6. Nge2 { [%cal Gh2h4] [%cal Ge2f4] [%csl Rg6] White wants to continue with **h4**. It is necessary to prepare this with } ( 6. Nge2 { , as the premature } ) ( 6. h4 { is met with } 6... h5 $1 { , when closing the kingside with } 7. g5 { gives Black a free hand on the other side: } 7... c5 { and Black already has good play. } ) 6... c5 { The typical break. } 7. Nf4 { This is rare, and for a good reason. } 7... Nc6 8. Nxg6 hxg6 { [%cal Gc5d4] [%cal Gc6d4] [%csl Rd4] White has managed to eliminate the Caro-Kann bishop, but it cost time and now their centre is under fire. } 9. Bb5 Ne7 { [%cal Ga7a6] [%cal Ge7c6] A new move. There were several other good candidates, but let's go with this. } 10. dxc5 a6 11. Ba4 { Keeping the pin is best. } 11... Qa5 { [%cal Ga5c5] [%cal Ge8c8] } 12. Bg5 Qxc5 { Regaining the pawn with good play. } * 

[Event "A Deep Dive into the Caro-Kann: Advance Variation for Black"]
[Site "4.Nc3 Shirov: 7.h4 with 9.g5 #1"]
