1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 { Positionally speaking, the knight is misplaced here, blocking the c-pawn. There is cunning idea behind } ( 4. Nc3 { , though. } ) 4... e6 5. g4 { The Shirov variation. White goes all-in on sharp play, trying to get the initiative with very aggressive moves. Black's structure is very firm and not so easy to overrun and modern engines confirm that this is a risky strategy for White. } 5... Bg6 6. Nge2 { [%cal Gh2h4] [%cal Ge2f4] [%csl Rg6] White wants to continue with **h4**. It is necessary to prepare this with } ( 6. Nge2 { , as the premature } ) ( 6. h4 { is met with } 6... h5 $1 { , when closing the kingside with } 7. g5 { gives Black a free hand on the other side: } 7... c5 { and Black already has good play. } ) 6... c5 { The typical break. } 7. h4 h5 $1 8. Nf4 Bh7 { Sacrificing the h-pawn. } ( 8... cxd4 9. Nxg6 fxg6 { is a playable alternative. } ) 9. Nxh5 cxd4 $1 { [%cal Gb8c6] I think this straightforward move is best. } ( 9... Nc6 { is a good alternative that has been played in many games. Critical is } 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Bg5 { and here } 11... Qb6 { leads to a complicated fight that is balanced according to the engines. } ) 10. Qxd4 { This looks very active, but the queen becomes a target and Black takes over. } 10... Nc6 { [%csl Rd4] [%csl Re5] } 11. Qa4 { The queen is not safe on a4 either. } 11... a6 { [%cal Gb7b5] [%csl Ga4] Preparing ...b5. } 12. Bg5 b5 $1 { Nice. } ( 12... f6 13. exf6 gxf6 14. Bd2 b5 15. Qf4 { is more messy. } ) 13. Qf4 { Keeping the queens on. } 13... Qc7 { [%cal Gc6e5] [%cal Gc7e5] [%csl Re5] Now e5 hangs. } 14. O-O-O Nge7 $1 { Playing for initiative instead of material. This is my key concept against the Shirov variation. Also: consider the psychology. White players who go for Nc3 and g4 like to attack and be in the drivers seat. When we force them to defend, they feel uncomfortable. } 15. Bxb5 { A typical active strike that you would expect, but it doesn't work. The engine proposes to take on **e7** with a balanced game: } ( 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 { when I still prefer Black, for instance } 16. Bd3 Bxd3 17. Rxd3 Qc7 { and again e5 is a target. } ) 15... axb5 16. Nxb5 Qa5 17. Nd6+ Kd7 18. Nxf7 Qc5 $1 { [%cal Ga8a2] [%cal Gc5c2] [%cal Gh7c2] [%csl Rc2] The most convincing reply. } 19. c3 Rxa2 20. Nxh8 Qb5 { [%cal Ga2a1] [%cal Gb5b2] [%csl Rb2] It's mate in a few moves. } * 

