1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 { Positionally speaking, the knight is misplaced here, blocking the c-pawn. There is cunning idea behind } ( 4. Nc3 { , though. } ) 4... e6 5. g4 { The Shirov variation. White goes all-in on sharp play, trying to get the initiative with very aggressive moves. Black's structure is very firm and not so easy to overrun and modern engines confirm that this is a risky strategy for White. } 5... Bg6 6. Nge2 { [%cal Gh2h4] [%cal Ge2f4] [%csl Rg6] White wants to continue with **h4**. It is necessary to prepare this with } ( 6. Nge2 { , as the premature } ) ( 6. h4 { is met with } 6... h5 $1 { , when closing the kingside with } 7. g5 { gives Black a free hand on the other side: } 7... c5 { and Black already has good play. } ) 6... c5 { The typical break. } 7. h4 h5 $1 8. Nf4 Bh7 { Sacrificing the h-pawn. } ( 8... cxd4 9. Nxg6 fxg6 { is a playable alternative. } ) 9. Nxh5 cxd4 $1 { [%cal Gb8c6] I think this straightforward move is best. } ( 9... Nc6 { is a good alternative that has been played in many games. Critical is } 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Bg5 { and here } 11... Qb6 { leads to a complicated fight that is balanced according to the engines. } ) 10. Qxd4 { This looks very active, but the queen becomes a target and Black takes over. } 10... Nc6 { [%csl Rd4] [%csl Re5] } 11. Bb5 { Pinning the knight. White keeps playing active moves. } 11... Ne7 $1 { [%cal Ge7c6] [%cal Ga7a6] Making sure that Black can take back on c6 with a knight. The plan is to play ...a6 next and force White to give the bishop. } 12. Bg5 { [%cal Gg5d8] [%cal Gb5e8] White pins the other black knight and keeps playing active moves. } 12... a6 $1 { A very precise reaction. } 13. Bxc6+ Nxc6 14. Qd2 Qb6 $1 { [%cal Gc6b4] [%csl Rb2] Black's initiative unfolds. } 15. O-O-O Nb4 { [%cal Gb4c2] [%cal Gh7c2] [%csl Rc2] Hitting c2. Black is winning. } 16. Qe3 Qa5 { [%cal Gb4a2] [%cal Ga5a2] [%cal Gb4c2] [%cal Gh7c2] It's possible to keep the queens on like this. White's king's position is being crushed. A sample line goes } 17. a3 Nxc2 18. Qf4 Nxa3 19. Qa4+ Qxa4 20. Nxa4 Rc8+ 21. Nc3 Nc4 { and Black is completely winning. We are even a pawn up. } * 

