1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 { Positionally speaking, the knight is misplaced here, blocking the c-pawn. There is cunning idea behind } ( 4. Nc3 { , though. } ) 4... e6 5. g4 { The Shirov variation. White goes all-in on sharp play, trying to get the initiative with very aggressive moves. Black's structure is very firm and not so easy to overrun and modern engines confirm that this is a risky strategy for White. } 5... Bg6 6. Nge2 { [%cal Gh2h4] [%cal Ge2f4] [%csl Rg6] White wants to continue with **h4**. It is necessary to prepare this with } ( 6. Nge2 { , as the premature } ) ( 6. h4 { is met with } 6... h5 $1 { , when closing the kingside with } 7. g5 { gives Black a free hand on the other side: } 7... c5 { and Black already has good play. } ) 6... c5 { The typical break. } 7. h4 h5 $1 8. Nf4 Bh7 { Sacrificing the h-pawn. } ( 8... cxd4 9. Nxg6 fxg6 { is a playable alternative. } ) 9. Nxh5 cxd4 $1 { [%cal Gb8c6] I think this straightforward move is best. } ( 9... Nc6 { is a good alternative that has been played in many games. Critical is } 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Bg5 { and here } 11... Qb6 { leads to a complicated fight that is balanced according to the engines. } ) 10. Qxd4 { This looks very active, but the queen becomes a target and Black takes over. } 10... Nc6 { [%csl Rd4] [%csl Re5] } 11. Bb5 { Pinning the knight. White keeps playing active moves. } 11... Ne7 $1 { [%cal Ge7c6] [%cal Ga7a6] Making sure that Black can take back on c6 with a knight. The plan is to play ...a6 next and force White to give the bishop. } 12. Bg5 { [%cal Gg5d8] [%cal Gb5e8] White pins the other black knight and keeps playing active moves. } 12... a6 $1 { A very precise reaction. } 13. Bxc6+ Nxc6 14. Qf4 { Covering the e5-pawn. } 14... Qa5 15. O-O { White must settle for this, but Black has a nice response that should appeal to real Caro-Kann players. } 15... Qb4 { [%cal Gb4g4] [%csl Rb2] [%csl Rf4] [%csl Rg4] Going for a nice ending. } ( 15... Bxc2 { is also possible. } ) 16. Qxb4 Nxb4 17. Rac1 Rc8 { [%cal Gc8c4] [%csl Rc2] Black will regain the pawn and have great piece play afterwards. The rook might use the c4-square and we have to admire our strong Caro-Kann bishop on h7. } * 

