1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 { Positionally speaking, the knight is misplaced here, blocking the c-pawn. There is cunning idea behind } ( 4. Nc3 { , though. } ) 4... e6 5. g4 { The Shirov variation. White goes all-in on sharp play, trying to get the initiative with very aggressive moves. Black's structure is very firm and not so easy to overrun and modern engines confirm that this is a risky strategy for White. } 5... Bg6 6. Nge2 { [%cal Gh2h4] [%cal Ge2f4] [%csl Rg6] White wants to continue with **h4**. It is necessary to prepare this with } ( 6. Nge2 { , as the premature } ) ( 6. h4 { is met with } 6... h5 $1 { , when closing the kingside with } 7. g5 { gives Black a free hand on the other side: } 7... c5 { and Black already has good play. } ) 6... c5 { The typical break. } 7. h4 h5 $1 8. Nf4 Bh7 { Sacrificing the h-pawn. } ( 8... cxd4 9. Nxg6 fxg6 { is a playable alternative. } ) 9. Nxh5 cxd4 $1 { [%cal Gb8c6] I think this straightforward move is best. } ( 9... Nc6 { is a good alternative that has been played in many games. Critical is } 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Bg5 { and here } 11... Qb6 { leads to a complicated fight that is balanced according to the engines. } ) 10. Bb5+ { A rare move that basically just helps Black. } 10... Nc6 11. Bxc6+ $5 ( 11. Qxd4 Ne7 { transposes to the line (See "the line" variation from the PGN) 10... cxd4 10.Qxd4 . } ) 11... bxc6 12. Qxd4 c5 { [%csl Rd4] Playing for the initiative. } ( 12... Bxc2 { is possible, but unclear after } 13. Bg5 { . } ) 13. Qa4+ { Retreating is unpleasant after } ( 13. Qd1 Rb8 { . Next Black will play ...Ne7 and ...Nc6 with great play for the pawn. } ) 13... Qd7 14. Nb5 { [%cal Gb5c7] The most tricky. } ( 14. Qxd7+ Kxd7 15. Kd1 Ne7 { followed by ...Nc6 leaves White in big trouble. } ) 14... Rb8 $1 { [%csl Rb5] } 15. c4 { The forcing } ( 15. Nd6+ Bxd6 16. Nxg7+ Kd8 17. Qxd7+ Kxd7 18. exd6 Bxc2 { is also good for Black, who will capture the d6-pawn. } ) 15... dxc4 16. Nd6+ Bxd6 17. Nxg7+ { The point. } 17... Kd8 18. Qxd7+ Kxd7 19. exd6 Nf6 $1 { [%cal Gf6g4] [%cal Gh8g8] [%csl Rg4] With active counterplay. Black is much better after } 20. f3 Rhg8 21. Bg5 Nd5 22. Nh5 Rxb2 23. Nf6+ Nxf6 24. Bxf6 Rg2 { when the rook on the second rank is extremely strong. } * 

