1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. g4 $5 { [%csl Rf5] White has had some success with this brutal move recently. Compared to the more sophisticated Shirov variation with } ( 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 { , this direct attack on the bishop looks more weakening than helpful. There are certain dangers - for both sides, you could add - so it is important to know what to do. } ) 4... Be4 $1 { [%csl Rh1] Forcing White to weaken the kingside with f3. In case of the immediate Black can consider } ( 4... Bg6 { White can play in many ways, for example } 5. Ne2 e6 6. Nf4 { . There is no reason to enter this. } ) ( 4... Bd7 { , which is a solid, but rather passive move. The idea is to play ...e6 next with a French type of position. I prefer to keep more tension, though. } ) 5. f3 Bg6 6. h4 { The main move, threatening to trap the bishop. } 6... h5 $1 { As we have seen so many times: h4 is strongly met by ...h5, not allowing White to grab a lot of space. } 7. Bd3 Bxd3 8. Qxd3 e6 { Black has a solid and sound structure. } 9. Bg5 { This makes sense, but Black's position can't be shaken. } 9... Be7 { [%cal Gh5g4] [%cal Ge7g5] The sharper } ( 9... Qb6 { is also interesting. } ) 10. Nd2 { White's alternatives give Black easy play: } ( 10. Bxe7 Nxe7 { followed by ...c5, or 10... Be7 10.Nh3 c5 11.dxc5 Qc7 and the e5-pawn hangs with check. } ) 10... hxg4 11. Bxe7 { This is forced. } 11... Qxe7 { [%cal Gh8h4] [%cal Ge7h4] [%csl Rh4] Now h4 hangs. } * 

