1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. g4 $5 { [%csl Rf5] White has had some success with this brutal move recently. Compared to the more sophisticated Shirov variation with } ( 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 { , this direct attack on the bishop looks more weakening than helpful. There are certain dangers - for both sides, you could add - so it is important to know what to do. } ) 4... Be4 $1 { [%csl Rh1] Forcing White to weaken the kingside with f3. In case of the immediate Black can consider } ( 4... Bg6 { White can play in many ways, for example } 5. Ne2 e6 6. Nf4 { . There is no reason to enter this. } ) ( 4... Bd7 { , which is a solid, but rather passive move. The idea is to play ...e6 next with a French type of position. I prefer to keep more tension, though. } ) 5. f3 Bg6 6. h4 { The main move, threatening to trap the bishop. } 6... h5 $1 { As we have seen so many times: h4 is strongly met by ...h5, not allowing White to grab a lot of space. } 7. Bd3 Bxd3 8. Qxd3 e6 { Black has a solid and sound structure. } 9. g5 { [%csl Rc1] [%csl Gf5] Closing the position secures White a lot of extra space, but it also makes the c1-bishop pretty bad and gives Black a nice square on f5. } 9... Ne7 10. Ne2 Nf5 { [%csl Gf5] Black is positionally better. } 11. g6 { This pawn sacrifice is White's only active possibility. } 11... c5 { [%cal Gb8c6] [%csl Rd4] Instead of taking the pawn, we can just play ...c5 with great play. } 12. gxf7+ Kxf7 { [%cal Gb8c6] [%csl Rd4] The king is safe here. Next up is ...Nc6 with pressure against d4. } * 

