1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. g4 $5 { [%csl Rf5] White has had some success with this brutal move recently. Compared to the more sophisticated Shirov variation with } ( 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 { , this direct attack on the bishop looks more weakening than helpful. There are certain dangers - for both sides, you could add - so it is important to know what to do. } ) 4... Be4 $1 { [%csl Rh1] Forcing White to weaken the kingside with f3. In case of the immediate Black can consider } ( 4... Bg6 { White can play in many ways, for example } 5. Ne2 e6 6. Nf4 { . There is no reason to enter this. } ) ( 4... Bd7 { , which is a solid, but rather passive move. The idea is to play ...e6 next with a French type of position. I prefer to keep more tension, though. } ) 5. f3 Bg6 6. h4 { The main move, threatening to trap the bishop. } 6... h5 $1 { As we have seen so many times: h4 is strongly met by ...h5, not allowing White to grab a lot of space. } 7. e6 { A strong pawn sacrifice. } ( 7. Ne2 e6 { transposes to the variation (See "the variation" variation from the PGN) 6... Bg6 6.Ne2 . } ) 7... Qd6 $1 { [%cal Gd6e6] Fortunately, we are not force to take the pawn. } ( 7... fxe6 8. Bd3 { gives White the initiative, though Black seems to be ok after } 8... Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Qd6 { . } ) 8. exf7+ Bxf7 { [%cal Gd6g3] } 9. Ne2 { Defending against ...Qg3+. There are no serious alternatives: • • • Finally, } ( 9. f4 { loses the g-pawn after } 9... Qe6+ { . } ) ( 9. g5 Qg3+ 10. Ke2 { has been seen, but looks awful for White. A good response is } 10... e6 11. Nh3 Qc7 { and Black is much better. } ) ( 9. Be3 { (So ...Qg3+ can be met by Bf2) } 9... Nd7 { gives Black control over the important e5-square. We can break with ...e5 at any moment. } ) 9... hxg4 10. fxg4 Nd7 { [%cal Ge7e5] Black is ready to strike with ...e5. } 11. Bf4 { The most played move. } ( 11. Nbc3 e5 { , with great play for Black, is no improvement for White. } ) 11... e5 $1 { Active counterplay. Don't go for } ( 11... Qb4+ 12. Nbc3 { when suddenly White has the initiative. } ) 12. dxe5 Nxe5 { [%cal Gg8f6] [%cal Gd6b4] [%csl Re1] [%csl Rg4] Black is much better. White has a bad king, the g4-pawn is loose and Black can develop quickly with ...Nf6. There are also ...Qb4+ ideas. All in all, it looks terrible for White! } * 

