1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nd2 { A popular positional line. White will make it hard for Black to get the strategic important ...c5 strike in. } 4... e6 5. Nb3 { [%cal Gb3c5] [%csl Gc5] The point of **4.Nd2**. } 5... Nd7 { [%cal Gc6c5] Fighting for ...c5. I have played the immediate } ( 5... c5 { . After } 6. dxc5 Bxc5 $1 7. Nxc5 Qa5+ 8. c3 Qxc5 9. Be3 Qc7 10. f4 Ne7 { White has the bishop pair, but Black is solid as was seen in Tari-Schandorff, Denmark 2020. } ) 6. Be3 { Still fighting for the c5-square. } 6... a5 $1 { [%cal Ga5a4] Black has played many things here. I like to throw in ...a5-a4. } 7. a4 f6 { [%csl Re5] The thematic attack on White's centre begins. If we can't get ...c5 in, then ...f6 is a natural way to get counterplay. } 8. f4 { Trying to keep everything together. } ( 8. Nf3 fxe5 9. Nxe5 Ngf6 { and } ) ( 8. exf6 Ngxf6 { both give Black active play and nothing to worry about. } ) 8... Bb4+ $1 { A very precise move. We want White to play c3. } 9. c3 ( 9. Bd2 fxe5 10. dxe5 Nc5 { is good for Black. } ) 9... Be7 10. Nf3 Nh6 11. Be2 Qb6 { [%cal Ge8g8] [%csl Rb3] Now the point of **8...Bb4+** is clear: the knight on b3 needs protection. [--] The position is complex, but I like Black's chances. We will castle short and try to use some of the weak squares on e4, f5 and g4. } * 

