1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nd2 { A popular positional line. White will make it hard for Black to get the strategic important ...c5 strike in. } 4... e6 5. Nb3 { [%cal Gb3c5] [%csl Gc5] The point of **4.Nd2**. } 5... Nd7 { [%cal Gc6c5] Fighting for ...c5. I have played the immediate } ( 5... c5 { . After } 6. dxc5 Bxc5 $1 7. Nxc5 Qa5+ 8. c3 Qxc5 9. Be3 Qc7 10. f4 Ne7 { White has the bishop pair, but Black is solid as was seen in Tari-Schandorff, Denmark 2020. } ) 6. Nf3 { White concentrates on development. } 6... a6 $5 { [%cal Gc6c5] [%csl Gb5] Black is covering the b5-square and is ready to strike with ...c5. This is a very direct approach. Black has tried almost all legal moves in the position. In my book Playing the Caro-Kann I gave } ( 6... Qc7 { is another good, flexible move. Next comes ...c5 or sometimes even ...f6. [--] The immediate strike } ) ( 6... c5 { is also possible. White can get the bishop pair, but not much more: } 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Nxc5 Qa5+ 9. c3 Qxc5 { This is quite similar to **5...c5**. } ) ( 6... Ne7 7. Be2 Nc8 { Using all squares! Next ...Be7 and ...O-O give Black a solid position. It is a bit passive, so for this course I have chosen something much more active! } ) 7. Be3 { Slowing Black down, but not really preventing the ...c5 break. } 7... Rc8 { [%cal Gc6c5] Some more preparation is needed. Next up is ...c5! } 8. c3 { Also } ( 8. Be2 c5 { is very similar to the mainline, no matter if White continues } 9. dxc5 { or } ( 9. c3 { . } ) ) 8... c5 9. dxc5 { Or } ( 9. Be2 h6 10. O-O c4 11. Nbd2 b5 { with a complicated position, similar to one that we will discuss later. } ) 9... Bxc5 10. Nxc5 Nxc5 11. Bxc5 { The most played move. Otherwise after } ( 11. Be2 { play is similar to the 7.Be2 mainline (See "the 7.Be2 mainline" variation from the PGN). } ) 11... Rxc5 12. Nd4 Ne7 { [%cal Ge8g8] [%cal Gd8c7] The position is equal. Also } ( 12... Bg6 { is fine. } ) * 

