closed nature of the position makes it difficult for both sides to navigate. I guess White should try to get some play on the kingside and Black can either play solidly or try to play on the queenside with the ...b4 break. } 11. Ne1 { Intending Nc2 and maybe f4 and g4. 11...Bh7Ν 12.f4 } 11... Ne7 { The move order matters: } ( 11... b4 { gives Black immediate counterplay and could be an improvement. } ) 12. f4 { The sharpest. } 12... Bh7 13. g4 { A critical position. } 13... b4 { Black has counterplay. } 14. Ng2 { The most logical. • After • • Finally, after } ( 14. f5 exf5 { it is not clear what White has for the pawn. } ) ( 14. cxb4 { is bad as after } 14... Nc6 { Black attacks both b4 and d4. } ) ( 14. Qa4 Qc7 { White can't take the pawn: } 15. Qxb4 $2 Nb6 { and ...Nc6 is coming. } ) 14... Qa5 15. Rf3 { [%csl Gc3] Defending c3, but losing some of the harmony which Black immediately exploits. } 15... h5 $1 16. h3 { If the **g4** -pawn is removed Black gets the nice **f5** -square. For example } ( 16. gxh5 Nf5 { with excellent positional compensation for the pawn. } ) 16... hxg4 17. hxg4 Nc6 { The opening of the h-file is to Black's advantage. White's king is in some danger. A sample line goes } 18. f5 { This is the only active attempt. } 18... Ndxe5 $1 19. dxe5 Bc5+ { Black is winning. } 20. Kf1 Bxf5 $1 21. gxf5 Rh1# { . } * 

