1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nd2 { A popular positional line. White will make it hard for Black to get the strategic important ...c5 strike in. } 4... e6 5. Nb3 { [%cal Gb3c5] [%csl Gc5] The point of **4.Nd2**. } 5... Nd7 { [%cal Gc6c5] Fighting for ...c5. I have played the immediate } ( 5... c5 { . After } 6. dxc5 Bxc5 $1 7. Nxc5 Qa5+ 8. c3 Qxc5 9. Be3 Qc7 10. f4 Ne7 { White has the bishop pair, but Black is solid as was seen in Tari-Schandorff, Denmark 2020. } ) 6. Nf3 { White concentrates on development. } 6... a6 $5 { [%cal Gc6c5] [%csl Gb5] Black is covering the b5-square and is ready to strike with ...c5. This is a very direct approach. Black has tried almost all legal moves in the position. In my book Playing the Caro-Kann I gave } ( 6... Qc7 { is another good, flexible move. Next comes ...c5 or sometimes even ...f6. [--] The immediate strike } ) ( 6... c5 { is also possible. White can get the bishop pair, but not much more: } 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Nxc5 Qa5+ 9. c3 Qxc5 { This is quite similar to **5...c5**. } ) ( 6... Ne7 7. Be2 Nc8 { Using all squares! Next ...Be7 and ...O-O give Black a solid position. It is a bit passive, so for this course I have chosen something much more active! } ) 7. Be2 { White just develops. This is the by far most popular move. } 7... c5 8. dxc5 { Opening up the position. This is White's most popular option. Otherwise Black might close the queenside with ...c4, which leads to some very original positions that are hard to judge. I think they are very playable for Black and give us good winning chances. } 8... Bxc5 { [%cal Gg8e7] Capturing with the bishop is best. After } ( 8... Nxc5 9. O-O { it is difficult for Black to develop the kingside. } ) 9. Nxc5 Nxc5 { [%cal Gg8e7] [%cal Ge8g8] So White got the bishop pair. Yes, but Black is ready to finish development with ...Ne7 and ...O-O. } 10. Nd4 { Hitting our other bishop. We are not forced to move it - defending it is fine. After } ( 10. O-O Ne7 { White doesn't have anything better than } 11. Nd4 { with a transposition. } ) 10... Ne7 { [%cal Ge7f5] [%cal Ge8g8] [%csl Gf5] The simplest. Possible as well is } ( 10... Bg6 11. O-O Ne7 { . } ) 11. O-O O-O 12. a4 Nd7 { [%cal Gd7e5] [%csl Re5] Going for counterplay. The standard } ( 12... Rc8 { is a more solid option and also fine. } ) 13. f4 f6 { [%cal Gf6e5] [%cal Gd7e5] [%csl Re5] Black insists. } 14. exf6 Rxf6 { [%cal Gf5e4] [%cal Ge7f5] [%cal Gf6g6] This is a very unclear position with chances for both sides. A sample lines goes } 15. b3 Be4 16. Bb2 Rg6 17. Rf2 Nf5 { with a balanced game. } * 

