} 11. Nd4 { with a transposition. } ) 10... Ne7 { [%cal Ge7f5] [%cal Ge8g8] [%csl Gf5] The simplest. Possible as well is } ( 10... Bg6 11. O-O Ne7 { . } ) 11. O-O O-O 12. Be3 Na4 { [%cal Ga4b2] [%csl Rb2] An unexpected move. Everybody plays } ( 12... Rc8 { , when a possible line goes } 13. a4 Nd7 14. f4 Be4 { followed by ...Nc6 or ...Nf5 and Black should be ok. } ) 13. Qc1 { Protecting the pawn. } 13... Rc8 14. c3 Qc7 { Black is fine. It is important to notice that we are not threatening to take on e5 yet because of Bf4. If Black was to move again, I like the little move ...h6, just improving the position and giving the bishop a retreat on h7 if necessary. White is hesitant to take on f5, though, because after Black takes back with Nxf5 the bishop on e3 becomes a target. } * 

