1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Be3 { Developing, protecting d4 and helping White to fight for the c5-square. Those are the positives of this move. In fact, however, the bishop is not that well placed on e3 and Black can often attack it with a knight from f5. This observation helps Black to form a good positional plan. } 4... e6 { Also possible is } ( 4... Qb6 { , which highlights another downside of **4.Be3** : the b2-pawn is not protected. } ) 5. Nd2 { The main move. White can also start with, Finally, } ( 5. Nf3 { but after } 5... Nd7 6. Nbd2 { we are back in the mainline. Also } ( 6. Be2 { is likely to transpose after } 6... Ne7 7. O-O h6 8. Nbd2 { . } ) ) ( 5. c3 { is covered in the **4.c3** chapter (See "chapter" variation from the PGN). } ) 5... Nd7 6. Ngf3 { The move } ( 6. Nb3 { transposes to lines covered in the 4.Nd2 chapter (See "the 4.Nd2 chapter" variation from the PGN). } ) 6... Ne7 { [%cal Gh7h6] [%cal Gf5h7] [%cal Ge7f5] With some sophisticated moves Black has just enough space to develop the kingside. Immediate counterplay with } ( 6... f6 { is strongly met by } 7. Bd3 $1 Bxd3 { and now the surprising } 8. cxd3 { after which I think White is slightly better. } ) 7. Be2 h6 { [%cal Gf5h7] [%cal Ge7f5] Please notice this nice regrouping. Black's problem is that the pieces want to use the same squares. Active counterplay with } ( 7... c5 { is possible, when White can answer } 8. dxc5 { or } ( 8. c4 { with a lot of tension in the centre, but I prefer to play more solidly. } ) ) 8. O-O Bh7 { [%cal Ge7f5] [%csl Gf5] The point. Now the e7-knight can go to f5. } 9. c4 Nf5 { This is Black's plan. } 10. cxd5 { White must create some play fast. } 10... cxd5 { It is possible to take on e3, but why do it immediately? } 11. Qb3 { [%csl Rb7] } 11... Rb8 $1 { A good human move. The engines believe Black can sacrifice the **b7** -pawn and just go } ( 11... Be7 12. Qxb7 Rb8 13. Qxa7 Nxe3 14. fxe3 Rxb2 { . The engines are probably right, but why play like this? } ) 12. Rfc1 Be7 { [%cal Ge8g8] [%cal Gf5e3] The position is equal. Black is ready to castle and take on **e3**. The game Hubner-Iordachescu, Germany 1997 continued } 13. Nf1 Nxe3 14. fxe3 O-O { and Black was even slightly better. } * 

