te wants to push f5 and attack. 13...f6Ν might be fine. } 13... O-O { An interesting position. } ( 13... f5 14. Bd3 { is risky for Black. However, } ) 14. f5 Rc8 { [%cal Gc6c5] Planning to strike with ...c5 with good counterplay. } 15. f6 { Or } ( 15. Bd3 c5 { and Black is fine. } ) 15... c5 $1 { This break comes just in time. } ( 15... gxf6 { might be playable. A possible continuation is } 16. exf6 Bxf6 17. Bxh6 Bg7 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Qd2 { and now } 19... Qh4 { with a complex - probably balanced - position. } ) 16. Nxc5 { Play becomes rather forced. } ( 16. fxg7 Kxg7 { will transpose if White takes on c5, and } 17. Qc1 Bg5 { is fine for Black. } ) 16... Nxc5 17. fxg7 { [%csl Rf8] The most precise. } ( 17. dxc5 { gives Black the extra option } 17... Qc7 $1 { . } ) 17... Kxg7 18. dxc5 Rxc5 { Here } ( 18... Qc7 { is no good because of } 19. Be3 { and Black can't take on e5: } 19... Qxe5 20. Bd4 { , winning the queen. } ) 19. Bd3 Rc8 { [%cal Gd8c7] [%csl Re5] The position is balanced. A sample line goes } 20. Bxh7 Kxh7 21. Be3 Qc7 22. Qd3+ Kg7 23. Qd2 Kh7 $1 { and White has nothing better than to repeat with } 24. Qd3+ { because } ( 24. Bxh6 Rg8 { might end badly for White. } ) * 

