1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. c3 { [%csl Gc3] [%csl Gd4] [%csl Ge5] White creates a strong pawn chain. This means that our standard break ...c5 loses some of its sting, but instead White's centre can be attacked from the front with ...f6. } 4... e6 5. Nf3 Nd7 { [%cal Gc6c5] [%cal Gf7f6] This is very flexible. } ( 5... c5 6. Be2 { could transpose to the Short variation, but of course White has other options as well. However, they are not dangerous: } ( 6. Bb5+ Nd7 $1 $2 7. O-O a6 { and Black has good play, or 6... c5 6.Be3 Qb6 when a high-profile blitz game went 7.Qa4+ Nc6 8.Bb5 (Aronian-Grischuk, 2020). Here I suggest the simple 8...Rc8 , played by Bogdan Lalic already back in 1994. Black has no problems. } ) ) 6. Bd3 Ne7 { [%cal Ge7f5] [%csl Gf5] Protecting the bishop. } 7. O-O c5 { Starting counterplay. Black can also try the waiting move } ( 7... h6 $1 $2 { . However, I don't want to be the one who takes first! } ) 8. dxc5 { Playing for the initiative. } ( 8. Be3 Qb6 { is fine for Black. } ) 8... Bxd3 { [%cal Gd7c5] Clever, so that ...Nxc5 comes with tempo. } 9. Qxd3 Nxc5 10. Qb5+ { After } ( 10. Qe2 { Black can just play ...Nc6 or try the flexible } 10... a6 $1 $2 { Ν, one point being that } 11. Be3 { can be met by } 11... Nf5 { . } ) 10... Nc6 { [%cal Gf8c5] [%cal Gf8e7] [%cal Ge8g8] [%cal Gd8b6] [%csl Gc5] Black is fine. A sample line goes } 11. Nd4 Qb6 $1 $2 { and we are happy if the queens are exchanged. } * 

