1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. c3 { [%csl Gc3] [%csl Gd4] [%csl Ge5] White creates a strong pawn chain. This means that our standard break ...c5 loses some of its sting, but instead White's centre can be attacked from the front with ...f6. } 4... e6 5. Nf3 Nd7 { [%cal Gc6c5] [%cal Gf7f6] This is very flexible. } ( 5... c5 6. Be2 { could transpose to the Short variation, but of course White has other options as well. However, they are not dangerous: } ( 6. Bb5+ Nd7 $1 $2 7. O-O a6 { and Black has good play, or 6... c5 6.Be3 Qb6 when a high-profile blitz game went 7.Qa4+ Nc6 8.Bb5 (Aronian-Grischuk, 2020). Here I suggest the simple 8...Rc8 , played by Bogdan Lalic already back in 1994. Black has no problems. } ) ) 6. Be2 { The most played move. White develops just like in the Short variation. } 6... a5 $5 { [%cal Ga5a4] We know this idea already. Also fine is the immediate confrontation } ( 6... f6 $1 $2 { . } ) 7. a4 { If White castles or plays Nbd2, Black goes ...a5-a4. } 7... f6 { Play will likely transpose to the Short variation (See "the Short variation" variation from the PGN). } * 

