1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. c3 { [%csl Gc3] [%csl Gd4] [%csl Ge5] White creates a strong pawn chain. This means that our standard break ...c5 loses some of its sting, but instead White's centre can be attacked from the front with ...f6. } 4... e6 5. Bd3 { We should always welcome an exchange of the light-squared bishops. There is no need to take, though. } 5... Ne7 { [%cal Ge7f5] [%cal Gf5d3] [%csl Gf5] } 6. Ne2 { The most played move. } 6... c5 { [%cal Gb8c6] } 7. O-O Nbc6 { [%cal Gf5d3] [%cal Ge7f5] [%cal Gf8e7] [%cal Ge8g8] Black has comfortably equalized. A sample line goes: } 8. a3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Nf5 10. b4 { This was White's plan. } 10... cxd4 11. cxd4 Be7 { Black has a good French. Of course, you need to take a little care. On the sharp } 12. f4 { I recommend } 12... h5 $1 { to secure the f5-knight from any g4-attacks. After } 13. Be3 O-O 14. Bf2 Qd7 15. Nd2 Rfc8 { Black is positionally better. White's bishop is bad. } * 

