1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. c3 { [%csl Gc3] [%csl Gd4] [%csl Ge5] White creates a strong pawn chain. This means that our standard break ...c5 loses some of its sting, but instead White's centre can be attacked from the front with ...f6. } 4... e6 5. Be3 { A logical follow-up. } 5... Qb6 { [%csl Rb2] This is always tempting as soon as White has moved the bishop from **c1**. The **b2** -pawn hangs. Other good possibilities are the flexible } ( 5... Nd7 { and even the immediate } ) ( 5... f6 { . However, I choose } ) ( 5... Qb6 { . } ) 6. Qb3 { A typical position with queens opposite each other. Neither player wants to be the one to take first and open the a-file for the opponent. } 6... Nd7 7. Nd2 f6 $1 { [%csl Re5] Going for immediate counterplay. The engine proposes } ( 7... h5 $1 $2 { , which also looks fine. } ) 8. Ngf3 { Developing should always be of high priority. } 8... Ne7 9. exf6 { White can't really keep the tension. } 9... gxf6 10. Nh4 { [%csl Rf5] Going after Black's bishop. Otherwise Black has just great play. } 10... Bg6 { [%cal Ge7f5] The simplest reply. In Playing the Caro-Kann I suggested the novelty } ( 10... a5 $1 $2 { , which still needs to be tested. The idea is to play ...a4 next and force White to take on b6, with an interesting endgame. } ) 11. Be2 Nf5 { [%cal Gf5e3] [%cal Gf5h4] [%cal Gf8d6] [%cal Gf8h6] Black is fine. An email game continued } 12. Nxf5 Bxf5 13. g4 Bg6 14. h4 h5 $1 { and Black fights for the key light squares with a good position. } * 

