1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Bd3 { [%cal Gd3f5] This is quite popular, especially at the club level. It is a simple move - probably too simple. Positionally speaking we don't mind exchanging light- squared bishops, hoping that White's remaing one on c1 will be rather bad in the long term. } 4... Bxd3 5. Qxd3 e6 { [%cal Gc6c5] } 6. Ne2 { An alternative to } ( 6. Nf3 { . The knight can later go to g3 or f4 and the other knight can use the f3-square. } ) 6... c5 { I tend to go for this break whenever it is good. Black could also play more flexibly with } ( 6... Nd7 { , } ) ( 6... Ne7 { or } ) ( 6... Qb6 { . } ) 7. c3 Nc6 8. O-O Qb6 { A typical move. } ( 8... Rc8 { has scored well for Black, but White can try to grab more space with } 9. a3 Nge7 10. b4 cxd4 11. cxd4 Nf5 12. Nd2 Be7 13. Nf3 { . Here Black must watch out for some g4-ideas. Probably it is fine, but I want to go in another direction. } ) 9. Nd2 cxd4 10. cxd4 Nb4 $1 { [%csl Rc2] [%csl Rd3] A simple solution. } 11. Qc3 Qb5 $1 { [%csl Re2] [%cal Gg8e7] [%cal Ga8c8] [%cal Gb5b4] [%csl Gb4] Black has good play. } 12. Nf4 { On } ( 12. Ng3 { we can force an ending with } 12... Qd3 { because after } 13. Qc7 Qb5 { White has nothing better than returning to c3. } ) 12... Ne7 { [%cal Ga8c8] ...Rc8 is next. } 13. Nf3 Rc8 14. Qb3 Qc4 { [%cal Gc4b3] [%cal Gc4c2] [%cal Ge7c6] Black has no problems. Also possible is } ( 14... a6 { , just protecting our queen. next the b4-knight can be moved. } ) * 

