1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Bd3 { [%cal Gd3f5] This is quite popular, especially at the club level. It is a simple move - probably too simple. Positionally speaking we don't mind exchanging light- squared bishops, hoping that White's remaing one on c1 will be rather bad in the long term. } 4... Bxd3 5. Qxd3 e6 { [%cal Gc6c5] } 6. Ne2 { An alternative to } ( 6. Nf3 { . The knight can later go to g3 or f4 and the other knight can use the f3-square. } ) 6... c5 { I tend to go for this break whenever it is good. Black could also play more flexibly with } ( 6... Nd7 { , } ) ( 6... Ne7 { or } ) ( 6... Qb6 { . } ) 7. c3 Nc6 8. O-O Qb6 { A typical move. } ( 8... Rc8 { has scored well for Black, but White can try to grab more space with } 9. a3 Nge7 10. b4 cxd4 11. cxd4 Nf5 12. Nd2 Be7 13. Nf3 { . Here Black must watch out for some g4-ideas. Probably it is fine, but I want to go in another direction. } ) 9. a3 { White goes for b4. This is a well-known idea in the French. It is also good here. } 9... Qa6 $5 { Keymer's nice idea. Of course, Black has many sensible alternatives, like } ( 9... cxd4 { or } ) ( 9... Nge7 { . } ) 10. Qd1 { The ending after } ( 10. Qxa6 bxa6 { is at least not worse for Black. The doubled a-pawns are not weak and White's bishop might be passive while Black has some nice light squares to work with. } ) 10... Nge7 11. b4 { This is the normal idea after a3, but here it doesn't work! Instead White should change the structure with } ( 11. dxc5 { , although after } 11... Nxe5 12. b4 b6 { Black was fine in Gomez-Krysa, Spain 2024. } ) 11... cxb4 12. cxb4 Nxb4 $1 { [%cal Ga6a1] [%csl Ra1] Using the pin on the a-file. Black wins a pawn. } * 

