1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Bd3 { [%cal Gd3f5] This is quite popular, especially at the club level. It is a simple move - probably too simple. Positionally speaking we don't mind exchanging light- squared bishops, hoping that White's remaing one on c1 will be rather bad in the long term. } 4... Bxd3 5. Qxd3 e6 { [%cal Gc6c5] } 6. Nf3 { A natural developing move. } ( 6. c3 { strengthens the pawn chain prophylactically, expecting ...c5. Black replies } 6... c5 { and after } 7. Ne2 { or } ( 7. Nf3 { play transposes to either **6.Ne2** or **6.Nf3**. } ) ) 6... c5 { [%csl Rd4] The usual strike. If you love endings, you can try The flexible } ( 6... Qa5+ { followed by ...Qa6. } ) ( 6... Nd7 7. O-O Ne7 { is probably ok too, but I prefer something more active. } ) 7. dxc5 { Tempting, because if Black takes back with the bishop then **8.Qb5+** wins a pawn. } 7... Bxc5 $1 { Anyway! This is good for Black, so there's no need to consider alternatives. } 8. Qb5+ Nd7 9. Qxb7 Ne7 { [%cal Ge8g8] [%cal Ge7g6] Black gets a lot of development for the pawn. } 10. O-O O-O 11. Nc3 { This has been tried in some games. 11...Nf5Ν could be considered. Black is ready to play ...Nd4 next. } 11... Ng6 { [%csl Re5] The new move } 12. Na4 { Kicking the bishop, but there is a tactical flaw. Better is } ( 12. Re1 Rb8 13. Qa6 { , but after } 13... Bb6 { Black has good play, which the engines confirm. Not just compensation - an advantage! } ) 12... Be7 13. Re1 Ndxe5 $1 { A nice combination. } 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Rxe5 Qd6 { [%cal Gd6e5] [%cal Gf8b8] [%csl Rb7] [%csl Re5] The point. The rook is attacked and Black threatens ...Rfb8, trapping the queen. An email game went } 16. Bf4 Rfb8 17. Rxe6 Qxf4 18. Qxe7 fxe6 19. Qxe6+ Kh8 { and Black won. } * 

