1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Bd3 { [%cal Gd3f5] This is quite popular, especially at the club level. It is a simple move - probably too simple. Positionally speaking we don't mind exchanging light- squared bishops, hoping that White's remaing one on c1 will be rather bad in the long term. } 4... Bxd3 5. Qxd3 e6 { [%cal Gc6c5] } 6. Nf3 { A natural developing move. } ( 6. c3 { strengthens the pawn chain prophylactically, expecting ...c5. Black replies } 6... c5 { and after } 7. Ne2 { or } ( 7. Nf3 { play transposes to either **6.Ne2** or **6.Nf3**. } ) ) 6... c5 { [%csl Rd4] The usual strike. If you love endings, you can try The flexible } ( 6... Qa5+ { followed by ...Qa6. } ) ( 6... Nd7 7. O-O Ne7 { is probably ok too, but I prefer something more active. } ) 7. dxc5 { Tempting, because if Black takes back with the bishop then **8.Qb5+** wins a pawn. } 7... Bxc5 $1 { Anyway! This is good for Black, so there's no need to consider alternatives. } 8. Qb5+ Nd7 9. Qxb7 Ne7 { [%cal Ge8g8] [%cal Ge7g6] Black gets a lot of development for the pawn. } 10. Qb5 { Returning with the queen makes sense. It loses time, though. } 10... O-O 11. O-O Qc7 { [%cal Ge7c6] [%cal Ge7f5] [%cal Ge7g6] [%csl Re5] A good square for the queen. The rooks are connected and e5 is a target. Moves like ...Nc6, ...Nf5 or ...Ng6 will follow. } 12. Qe2 Ng6 13. Re1 { Covering e5. } 13... f6 $1 { Going for the initiative. } ( 13... h6 { with long-term compensation is also playable. } ) 14. exf6 Nxf6 $1 { [%cal Ga8e8] } 15. Be3 e5 16. Bxc5 Qxc5 { [%csl Gd5] [%csl Ge5] Black's strong centre gives good play for the pawn. A sample line is } 17. Nc3 e4 18. Ng5 Rfe8 { and Black is better. } * 

