1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Bd3 { [%cal Gd3f5] This is quite popular, especially at the club level. It is a simple move - probably too simple. Positionally speaking we don't mind exchanging light- squared bishops, hoping that White's remaing one on c1 will be rather bad in the long term. } 4... Bxd3 5. Qxd3 e6 { [%cal Gc6c5] } 6. Nf3 { A natural developing move. } ( 6. c3 { strengthens the pawn chain prophylactically, expecting ...c5. Black replies } 6... c5 { and after } 7. Ne2 { or } ( 7. Nf3 { play transposes to either **6.Ne2** or **6.Nf3**. } ) ) 6... c5 { [%csl Rd4] The usual strike. If you love endings, you can try The flexible } ( 6... Qa5+ { followed by ...Qa6. } ) ( 6... Nd7 7. O-O Ne7 { is probably ok too, but I prefer something more active. } ) 7. c3 Nd7 { [%cal Gg8e7] [%cal Ge7c6] Most people go for } ( 7... Nc6 { , but this is clever: the g8-knight is heading for c6 with a very harmonious position. } ) 8. O-O Ne7 9. Bg5 { Pinning the knight. } ( 9. Be3 Nc6 10. Nbd2 Be7 { is comfortable for Black. } ) 9... h6 { A very simple solution. It's not the only good move, though. } ( 9... Qb6 { Attacking b2. } 10. Nbd2 Nc6 { and Black is also more than fine. } ) 10. Bxe7 { Bad for White is } ( 10. Bh4 g5 11. Bg3 Nf5 { when Black is ready to follow up with ...h5 with a strong initiative. } ) 10... Bxe7 { [%cal Ge8g8] [%cal Gc5d4] [%cal Gd8b6] [%csl Ge7] Black is slightly better. The dark-squared bishop is strong. It can attack White's centre in an ending, and White's knights lack good outposts. A sample line goes } 11. Nbd2 cxd4 12. cxd4 Qb6 { followed by ...O-O and a rook to the c-file. } * 

