1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Ne2 { [%cal Ge2g3] [%cal Ge2f4] [%csl Rf5] This looks clumsy at first sight. However, the knight has no intention of staying on e2. It will go to g3 and harass our Caro-Kann bishop. } 4... e6 5. Nf4 { [%cal Gg2g4] This looks strange at first, but then you realize that White intends to follow up with g4. } 5... c5 $1 { Still, we play this break whenever we can. } 6. g4 { The point. } 6... Be4 $1 { [%csl Rh1] } 7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. Bxc6+ { White must simplify. Not } ( 8. O-O Ne7 { and Black is much better. } ) 8... bxc6 9. f3 Bg6 { Here the check on h4 is not so clear. Just returning the bishop is simple and good, however. } 10. h4 h5 $1 { A standard reaction to White's h4. We see it again and again. } 11. Nxg6 fxg6 { [%cal Gc5d4] [%cal Gc6c5] Black is better despite the somewhat damaged pawn structure. Play can continue } 12. Qd3 cxd4 $1 { Ν } 13. Qxg6+ Kd7 14. Bg5 Ne7 { when Black's king is safe on d7 and the d4-pawn can be protected with ...c5. Black can attack White's e5-pawn and use the open b-file to put pressure on the queenside. } * 

