1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Bf4 { The bishop is pretty bad on c1. The question is if it is much better on f4! } 4... Qb6 { [%csl Rb2] We have seen this many times in the course: as soon as Bc1 leaves its post Black can play the annoying ...Qb6, hitting b2. The normal move } ( 4... e6 { is , of course, also fine. } ) 5. b3 { Best. Stockfish has } ( 5. Bc1 { as the second best. This is a bad sign for White! } ) 5... e6 { Black is already very comfortable. } 6. Nf3 c5 { [%cal Gb8c6] [%cal Gf5g4] [%csl Rd4] The typical break. Black has the initiative. A sample line goes } 7. c3 Bg4 $1 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Bg3 Nc6 10. b4 Bxf3 $1 11. Qxf3 Nxb4 $1 $2 12. cxb4 Bd4 13. Nc3 Qxb4 14. Rc1 Rc8 15. Bb5+ Kf8 16. O-O Rxc3 { and Black has won two pawns. Of course the king is not optimal on f8, but the line looks pretty good. If you don't like it, you can deviate with **11...Be7**. } * 

[Event "A Deep Dive into the Caro-Kann: Advance Variation for Black"]
[Site "Rare 4th Moves: 4.f4 #1"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Rare 4th Moves: 4.f4 #1"]
[Black "24) 4.f4 and Rare 4th Moves"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. f4 { [%csl Rc1] This has been played in almost 1.000 games. I must admit that I am a bit surprised about this. White does nothing to fight for the light squares and the pawn on f4 doesn't exactly improve the future of the c1-bishop. If you look at a big database there are always some random moves. Here I will mention a few of them. } ( 4. a3 { is a legal move, but it doesn't accomplish much. After } 4... e6 { Black just plays normal moves and gets a fine position. } ) ( 4. Be2 { Sometimes White uses this move order. It has no independent relevance, because after } 4... e6 5. Nf3 { play transposes to the Short variation (See "Short variation" variation from the PGN). } ) 4... e6 5. Nf3 c5 { [%csl Rd4] This is the way we play in most lines, so also here. Black has many other options. I also like } ( 5... h5 $1 $2 { followed by ...Nh6 with good control over the light squares. } ) 6. Be3 { Fighting for the initiative. We have seen a similar idea in the Short variation. White wants to force Black to take on d4 and then recapture with the knight, attacking our f5-bishop. } 6... Qb6 $1 { [%csl Rb2] Exploiting the weak b2-pawn. } 7. Nc3 { White plays for initiative. } ( 7. b3 Nc6 { is just good for Black. Best is likely 7... Qb6 7.dxc5 , but surely Black has no problems after 7...Bxc5 . } ) 7... c4 { [%cal Gb8c6] [%cal Gh7h5] The engine wants to take on **b2** , no surprise! With the nice move } ( 7... c4 { Black closes the position and keeps good chances in a long maneuvering game. A sample line goes } 8. Rb1 Nc6 9. Be2 h5 10. O-O Nh6 { and next is ...Be7 or ...Bb4. Black keeps the king in the centre for the time being to find out which way the wind blows. } ) * 

