1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. f4 { [%csl Rc1] This has been played in almost 1.000 games. I must admit that I am a bit surprised about this. White does nothing to fight for the light squares and the pawn on f4 doesn't exactly improve the future of the c1-bishop. If you look at a big database there are always some random moves. Here I will mention a few of them. } ( 4. a3 { is a legal move, but it doesn't accomplish much. After } 4... e6 { Black just plays normal moves and gets a fine position. } ) ( 4. Be2 { Sometimes White uses this move order. It has no independent relevance, because after } 4... e6 5. Nf3 { play transposes to the Short variation (See "Short variation" variation from the PGN). } ) 4... e6 5. Nf3 c5 { [%csl Rd4] This is the way we play in most lines, so also here. Black has many other options. I also like } ( 5... h5 $1 $2 { followed by ...Nh6 with good control over the light squares. } ) 6. c3 { Protecting the centre. This is the most played move. } ( 6. Bb5+ { only helps Black to develop: } 6... Nc6 { and it's not clear what White is doing. } ) ( 6. Bd3 Nh6 { is just good for Black. } ) 6... Nc6 7. Bb5 { At least this looks threatening. } ( 7. Be3 Qb6 { and 7... Nc6 7.Bd3 Nh6 both give Black an easy game. } ) 7... h5 { [%cal Gg8h6] I like suggesting completely new directions. Black intends to play ...Nh6. The most played is the natural } ( 7... Qb6 { , which is also good. } ) 8. O-O Nh6 { [%cal Gf5g4] [%cal Gh6f5] [%cal Gd8b6] [%cal Gf8e7] [%csl Gf5] [%csl Gh6] Black is better with good control over the light squares on the kingside. } * 

