1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Nd7 6. O-O a5 7. Nc3 { This game shows what can happen if Black is allowed to advance the a-pawn. } 7... a4 8. Bd2 a3 { It keeps moving! In the theory section (See "theory section" variation from the PGN) I recommend to leave it on **a4** and play } ( 8... h6 { immediately. Still, it is interesting to see how play can develop if the position is completely closed to begin with. } ) 9. b3 { White must close the queenside. Otherwise their structure will be severely damaged. } 9... h6 { [%cal Gf5h7] A standard move that gives the f5-bishop a retreat on h7. The more active } ( 9... Bb4 $1 $2 { was possible. If } 10. Nb5 { then } 10... Be7 11. Nd6+ Bxd6 12. exd6 Ndf6 13. Bb4 Ne4 { and the d6-pawn falls with an unclear game. } ) 10. Rc1 Ne7 11. h3 Bh7 12. Bd3 { I don't know about this move. The engine prefers } ( 12. Na4 { and claims White is better. } ) 12... Bxd3 13. cxd3 Qb6 14. Be3 Ng6 { A very complicated position. The next phase is very illustrative: Black plays rather solidly and hopes to exploit the long-term advantages based on the better structure. Keymer succeeds in a very convincing way and gives a helping hand to all Caro-Kann players by showing how to play in a very closed position. } 15. Nh2 { [%cal Gf2f4] Intending f4. White still plays for the initiative. } 15... Be7 16. f4 Nh4 $1 { [%csl Gf5] Stopping your opponent's plan is always worth considering. } 17. Nf3 Nxf3+ ( 17... Nf5 18. Bf2 h5 { is also fine for Black. } ) 18. Qxf3 g6 $1 { Again, Black prevents f5. } 19. Rc2 { Or } ( 19. g4 h5 $1 ) 19... h5 20. g3 Nb8 $1 { [%cal Gb8a6] [%cal Ga6b4] [%csl Ga2] [%csl Gd3] A nice regrouping. The knight goes to a6 from where it can jump to b4 and perhaps attack the weak a2-pawn. } 21. g4 Na6 22. f5 { White has managed to get their kingside play going after all. However, it turns out that this merely helps Black. } 22... hxg4 23. hxg4 Kd7 { A strong move. Perhaps } ( 23... gxf5 24. gxf5 O-O-O { would have been even more convincing. Black is much better. } ) 24. f6 ( 24. fxe6+ fxe6 25. Qf7 { is met by } 25... Raf8 26. Qxg6 Rfg8 27. Qf7 Rxg4+ 28. Rg2 Rxg2+ 29. Kxg2 Qd8 $1 { and Black is ready to exchange queens with ...Qg8+, with a great ending. } ) 24... Bb4 25. Na4 Qb5 26. Bc1 Qa5 27. Kg2 Rh7 { Black exploits the open h-file to get a strong attack. } 28. Be3 Rah8 { [%csl Gh2] } 29. Bg1 Qd8 $1 { [%cal Gd8g8] [%cal Gh7h1] [%cal Gg8h7] The queen joins the action. Black wants to play ...Qg8, ...Rh1 and ...Qh7. White's position is already hopeless. } 30. Nc5+ Bxc5 31. dxc5 Nb4 32. Re2 Qf8 33. d4 Qh6 34. Qc3 Qg5 35. Kf2 Rh3 0-1 

