1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Nd7 { I recommend we start with . Usually } ( 5... Nd7 { and then } 6. -- a5 { just transposes, though. } ) 6. O-O a5 7. a4 f6 { Attacking the centre head on is a key idea in this system. } 8. Nbd2 Nh6 { [%cal Gh6f7] [%csl Ge5] A splendid activation of the knight: it will be great on f7 where it hits the important e5-pawn. } 9. Nb3 Nf7 10. Re1 g5 $1 { Going for active play. Black is ready to follow up with ...Bg7. } 11. exf6 { Often Black can be happy if White takes on f6, because it opens up extra squares for the black pieces. The queen is good on f6 and the bishop gets the excellent d6-square. Better is } ( 11. Bd2 { , as shown in the theory section (See "theory section" variation from the PGN). } ) 11... Qxf6 12. Bd3 { Opening the e-file. } 12... Bxd3 13. Qxd3 g4 $1 14. Nfd2 { White should have tried the spectacular } ( 14. Nh4 { , but without engine analysis it is hard to play like this. After all, the knight is en prise! It is very dangerous to take it, so I suggest } 14... Be7 $1 15. g3 e5 { with good play. } ) 14... h5 { Black has promising play. } 15. Qe2 { [%csl Ge6] } 15... Nd8 ( 15... e5 { is also good. } ) 16. Nf1 Bd6 17. Bd2 b6 18. c4 O-O 19. Rac1 Qg6 { Black keeps improving their position. White can still keep the balance with exact play, but it is getting harder and harder. } 20. Bc3 { The right move was } ( 20. Qe3 { , intending to exchange queens, and if } 20... Bf4 21. Qe2 { and the position is still equal. } ) 20... Nf6 { [%cal Gf6e4] The knight can jump to e4. Now Black is much better. } 21. c5 bxc5 22. dxc5 Bc7 23. Be5 Bxe5 24. Qxe5 Ne4 25. Ng3 Ng5 $1 { The rook on a8 can be activated via a7 and White's queen can be kicked away with ...Nf7. } 26. Nd4 h4 27. Nge2 Ndf7 28. Qf4 e5 { Even stronger is } ( 28... Rac8 { . } ) 29. Qf5 Qxf5 30. Nxf5 Ra7 31. Nxh4 Rb8 { Black has a huge intiative, even in the ending, but objectively it was better to keep the queens on the board! } 32. Rc2 Rab7 { [%csl Gb2] } 33. Nf5 Kf8 { [%csl Ge7] } 34. Rb1 Rb4 35. Neg3 e4 36. Ne2 Ne6 37. Rd2 Ne5 38. Ned4 Nxd4 39. Nxd4 Rxa4 { Restoring material equality. Black's dominant pieces decide the game. } 40. b3 Rab4 { Black could have won with } ( 40... Nd3 $1 { , exploiting the pin on the b-file and the weak back rank: } 41. Nxc6 Rxb3 $1 42. Rdd1 Rxb1 43. Rxb1 Nxc5 { and the d-pawn comes forward. } ) 41. Ra1 Ra8 42. h4 gxh3 43. Kh2 hxg2 44. Kxg2 a4 45. bxa4 Raxa4 46. Rxa4 Rxa4 47. Nxc6 { White's best chance. } 47... Nxc6 48. Rxd5 Kf7 { White can't eliminate the last black pawn. } 49. Kg3 Ne7 $1 50. Rd1 Ke6 51. Re1 Ke5 52. Kg4 { Or } ( 52. f3 Nf5+ { and ...e3. } ) 52... Rc4 53. Re2 { Not } ( 53. f3 e3+ { . } ) 53... Nd5 54. Ra2 Rxc5 55. Ra8 Rc6 56. Ra5 Rg6+ 57. Kh3 Rg5 58. Kh2 Kf4 59. Ra3 Nf6 60. Ra6 Nd7 61. Ra3 Ne5 62. Ra8 Nd3 63. Ra2 Kf3 64. Rc2 Rg2+ 65. Kh3 Nf4+ 66. Kh4 Rg4# 0-1 

