1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 c5 { This active counterstrike has always been a favourite of mine. } 6. Be3 { The critical response. } 6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 Ne7 { [%csl Gf5] A key move. Instead of moving **Bf5** , Black just defends the bishop. We are not afraid of } 8. Bg5 $5 { Losing time, but pinning the e7-knight and thus threatening Nxf5. The immediate White's main moves are } ( 8. Nxf5 { . } ) ( 8. Nxf5 Nxf5 { hits the e3-bishop and is fine for Black. } ) ( 8. Nd2 { , } ) ( 8. c4 { and } ) ( 8. O-O { . } ) 8... Qd7 $1 9. Bxe7 Bxe7 10. Nxf5 exf5 { [%csl Gd5] [%csl Gf5] [%csl Gf7] This is the reason I want to show this game. If you have never seen this structure before, it can be hard to judge. Black's pawns are not weak - this is the big point! } 11. Bf3 Qb5 $1 { [%cal Gb5b2] A nice counter-attack. } 12. Qxd5 Qxb2 13. O-O ( 13. Qxb7 Bb4+ $1 { wins for Black: } 14. Kf1 O-O 15. g3 Nc6 $1 16. Bxc6 Rab8 17. Qxa7 Qxa1 18. Kg2 Qxe5 { . } ) 13... Nc6 { This has been played in a couple of games and the conclusion is clear: Black is absolutely fine. } 14. Qb3 ( 14. Nd2 { is also nothing for White. For starters, the e5-pawn is hanging. } ) 14... Qxe5 15. Qxb7 O-O $1 16. Nd2 Bd6 { [%csl Gh2] Threatening mate. } 17. g3 Nd4 { Black is very active. } 18. Nc4 Qf6 19. Qxa8 { Probably a mistake. The c-pawn was hanging and } ( 19. c3 Rab8 20. Qd5 Nxf3+ 21. Qxf3 Bc5 { is also somewhat unpleasant for White. } ) 19... Rxa8 20. Bxa8 Bc5 { Black will get a strong initiative. It is hard for White to activate the rooks, and they are just poor defenders. } 21. Rae1 g6 22. c3 Ne6 23. Re5 f4 { Black's chances are on the kingside. We see the advantage of having two f-pawns! } 24. Bd5 Ng5 $1 { It was an email game, so long precise calculations are indeed possible. } 25. h4 Nh3+ 26. Kg2 Nxf2 $1 27. Rxf2 Bxf2 28. Kxf2 Kf8 { White has a lot of pieces for the queen, but they are badly coordinated and the queen can jump around and attack all the soft spots. } 29. Bf3 Qa6 { [%csl Ga2] [%csl Gc4] } 30. Bd5 Qxa2+ 31. Kf3 Qc2 { [%csl Gc3] } 32. gxf4 Qd1+ 33. Ke4 h5 { Of course, White has drawing chances, but the queen is really strong. Anyway, we can conclude that Black won the opening duel! } 34. Nd6 Qb1+ 35. Kf3 Qd3+ 36. Kf2 Qd2+ 37. Kg3 Qxc3+ 38. Bf3 Qa1 39. Nb7 Qg1+ 40. Bg2 Qd1 41. Bf3 Qc1 42. Na5 f6 43. Re6 Qg1+ 44. Bg2 Qb1 45. Re4 Qb5 46. Nb7 a5 47. Bf3 a4 48. Nd6 Qd7 49. Nc4 Qa7 50. Re3 a3 51. Rxa3 Qg1+ 52. Bg2 Qe1+ 53. Kf3 Qd1+ 54. Ke3 Qc1+ 55. Kd3 Qxf4 56. Bd5 Kg7 57. Ra7+ Kh6 0-1 

