1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bd3 Bxd3 6. Qxd3 Qa5+ 7. Nd2 { The main move after 6...Qa5+. } 7... e6 8. Nf3 Nh6 { [%csl Gf5] Going to f5. This highlights the downside of White's entire plan with 3. e5, 4. h4 and 5. Bd3: the light squares are weak and Black can use them with the knights. } 9. O-O Nf5 10. Nb3 { Using Black's queen to gain a tempo. White wants to get the bishop out to **g5**. Alternatives are } ( 10. c4 { and } ) ( 10. a4 { . } ) 10... Qa6 11. Qd1 { Exchanging the queens would give up all hopes of getting an opening advantage. } 11... b6 $1 { [%cal Gc6c5] Black needs to get ...c5 in. } 12. Bg5 c5 13. dxc5 { If White doesn't take, Black just increase the pressure on d4 with ...Nc6. } 13... Bxc5 { I prefer this recapture. Getting the pieces out is important. } 14. c3 Nc6 15. Re1 Rc8 $1 { [%cal Gc8c7] [%cal Gc7d7] A key move worth remembering. Castling too soon might give White some attacking chances. Black is ready to start with some intelligent waiting moves, like improving the rook further with Rc8-c7-d7. } 16. Nxc5 bxc5 17. b3 Rc7 $1 18. Qd2 Rd7 { [%csl Ge8] The first part of the regrouping is concluded. Please notice that Black still keeps the king in the centre. } 19. Red1 Qb7 { Now the moment has come to improve the queen. } 20. Rac1 a5 { Here } ( 20... O-O { is also fine, but Black apparently decides to play a waiting game. } ) 21. Qe2 Qb8 22. g3 Qb7 23. Bf4 Rd8 24. Ne1 { Better is } ( 24. Be3 { , hitting c5. } ) 24... a4 $1 { [%csl Gb3] Creating a target on the queenside. } 25. Rb1 axb3 26. axb3 Rb8 27. Kh2 d4 { Finally Black goes for the initiative. } 28. c4 Nb4 29. Nd3 Nxd3 30. Rxd3 Qa8 31. Rd2 Rb6 32. Ra2 Qb7 33. Rba1 O-O $1 { Black castles on move 33 and is immediately better! } 34. Ra7 Qc6 35. Qd3 Rfb8 36. R1a3 R6b7 37. R7a6 Qc7 38. Qf3 Qd7 $5 39. Qxh5 d3 { [%csl Gd4] Black has great compensation for the pawn. The queen and the knight can use the d4-square to penetrate White's position, and we shouldn't forget about the passed pawn either. } 40. Qd1 Qd4 41. Kh3 $6 Qe4 $1 { Black completely dominates the position. } 42. R6a5 Qe2 43. Qd2 ( 43. Qxe2 dxe2 44. Bd2 Nd4 { and Black wins. } ) 43... Nd4 $6 ( 43... Qf1+ { wins almost immediately: } 44. Kh2 Nd4 45. Qe3 d2 { and it is time for White to resign. } ) 44. b4 $1 { [%csl Gd3] } 44... Qf1+ 45. Kg4 $1 Qe2+ 46. Kh3 cxb4 47. Rxd3 { Eliminating the strong d-pawn, but Black has another asset. } 47... b3 48. Rxd4 Qf1+ 49. Kg4 b2 50. Rd8+ Kh7 51. Qc2+ g6 52. Rd1 b1=Q 53. Rxb1 Rxb1 54. h5 $2 { White could have kept the balance with } ( 54. Ra7 Kg8 55. Be3 { . } ) 54... Qh1 $1 { [%csl Gg4] White's king is in danger. Now Black is winning again. } 55. hxg6+ fxg6 { [%cal Gh1h5] } 56. Ra7+ R1b7 57. Rxb7+ Rxb7 58. Kg5 { Or } ( 58. Bg5 Rf7 59. Bh4 Qf3+ 60. Kh3 Rd7 { followed by ...Rd1. } ) 58... Kg8 $1 { Not } ( 58... Qh5+ 59. Kf6 { and Black doesn't have any checks. } ) 59. Kf6 ( 59. Qxg6+ Rg7 { . } ) 59... Rf7+ 60. Kxe6 { White resigned before Black could play } 60... Qc6# { mate! } 0-1 

