1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. c4 { This tempting attack on Black's centre is very popular, with or without the moves h4-h5 thrown in. } 5... e6 6. Nc3 dxc4 $1 { [%csl Gd5] An important strategic decision. Black changes the structure to get a nice square on d5. } 7. Bxc4 Nd7 8. Nge2 { The most flexible. } ( 8. Nf3 { allows } 8... Bg4 { , while 8... Nd7 8.Bg5 is simply met by 8...Be7 . } ) 8... Be7 { [%csl Gh4] Hitting the h4-pawn. } 9. g3 { Just protecting. White could go for the black h-pawn with } ( 9. Ng3 Bg6 10. Be2 { , but after } 10... Qb6 $1 { Black has excellent counterplay, as you can see in the theory section (See "theory section" variation from the PGN). } ) 9... Nh6 10. Bf4 ( 10. Bxh6 Rxh6 { is fine for Black. } ) 10... Qb6 11. O-O Rd8 $1 { Putting White's centre under pressure. } 12. Qc1 a6 { [%cal Gc6c5] Preparing ...c5. } 13. Be3 { White could try } ( 13. Bb3 { , but after } 13... Ng4 { anything can happen in this unclear position. You can see more in the theory section (See "theory section" variation from the PGN). } ) 13... c5 $1 { Black takes over. } 14. Rd1 { There were no really good moves for White. For example } ( 14. dxc5 Bxc5 { or } ) ( 14. d5 Nxe5 { . } ) 14... Ng4 $1 15. Bb3 O-O { White can't keep the centre intact anymore. } 16. dxc5 Bxc5 17. Na4 { Or } ( 17. Bxc5 Nxc5 18. Qf4 Nd3 { and wins. } ) 17... Bxe3 $1 { The only move, but a simple one. } 18. Nxb6 Bxc1 { Keeping it simple in a winning position. } ( 18... Bxf2+ 19. Kf1 Bxb6 { is also winning according to the machine. } ) 19. Nxd7 Bxb2 20. Nxf8 Rxf8 { The final point. White can't save the rook in the corner. } 21. Nd4 Bg6 22. Rac1 Nxe5 0-1 

