1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 { The sharp Shirov variation. Please compare the opening with the next Model Game and check the theory as well. } 5... Bg6 6. Nge2 c5 7. h4 h5 $1 { Stopping White's expansion. } 8. Nf4 Bh7 $1 { Sacrificing the h-pawn. Black fights hard for the initiative. In the next Model Game (See "next Model Game" variation from the PGN) you can see more comments to the following moves. } 9. Nxh5 cxd4 10. Qxd4 Nc6 11. Bb5 Ne7 12. Bh6 { [%csl Gg7] This spectacular move is the reason I am showing this game. If you have never seen it before, you might fall off your chair if your opponent is blitzing it out! } 12... Rg8 $1 { [%csl Gg7] Very cool. Black just defends g7. The position after } ( 12... gxh6 13. Nf6# { is nice, but since this is a black repertoire I suggest we avoid it! } ) 13. O-O-O a6 $1 { Breaking the pin. } 14. Bxc6+ Nxc6 15. Qf4 Qa5 { [%cal Gh7c2] [%csl Gc2] [%csl Gh7] Black's initiative on the queenside is very strong. It makes sense to compare it with my game (See "my game" variation from the PGN) against Aabling, which I will show next. Please notice our strong Caro-Kann bishop operating from a long distance and playing a vital role in the coming onslaught. } 16. Rhe1 { Better is } ( 16. Rh3 { , but Black still gets promising play after } 16... Rc8 $1 { . } ) 16... Nb4 $1 { [%csl Ga2] [%csl Gc2] Attacking a2 and c2. } 17. Qg5 { Rather desperate, but there was nothing good for White. } 17... Nxa2+ 18. Nxa2 Rc8 $1 { [%csl Gc2] Really nice. } 19. Bxg7 { Or } ( 19. Nc3 Rxc3 20. bxc3 Qxc3 { and it is over: } 21. Re2 Ba3+ 22. Kb1 Qb2# { . } ) 19... Rxc2+ 20. Kb1 Be7 $1 { The only move that wins, but another brilliant idea. } 21. Nf6+ Bxf6 22. exf6 Re2+ { The rook on e1 is hanging. } 23. Ka1 Rxe1 24. Rxe1 Qxe1+ 25. Qc1 Qxc1+ 26. Nxc1 Kd7 { [%cal Gg8c8] [%cal Gc8c4] [%cal Gc4c2] [%csl Gg8] Liberating Black's rook. It is game over. } 27. h5 Rc8 28. Nb3 Rc4 29. Bf8 Rxg4 30. Be7 b6 0-1 

