1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 { The sharp Shirov Variation. I don't know about you, but I am happy if White tries to play extremely aggressively, because the Caro-Kann structure is just so firm that it is hard to believe that it can be overrun so easily. [--] That being said, in many modern openings White plays g4. Here the story is somewhat different, though. If Black gets ...c5 in, White can't hold the centre and the knight on c3 turns out to be misplaced. } 5... Bg6 6. Nge2 c5 $1 7. h4 h5 $1 { A necessary but strong pawn sacrifice. } 8. Nf4 Bh7 9. Nxh5 Nc6 { Already White's centre is under attack. } 10. Bb5 { [%cal Gb5e8] [%csl Gd4] Using the pin to secure the d4-square, but it is just a matter of time before Black gets rid of the bishop. } 10... cxd4 11. Qxd4 Ne7 { [%cal Ge7c6] So we can take back on c6 with the knight. } 12. Bg5 a6 $1 { The tactics work for Black. } 13. Bxc6+ Nxc6 { [%csl Gd4] [%csl Gd8] } 14. Qf4 Qa5 { Black has good play. } 15. O-O-O { The natural follow-up, but it loses. As you can see in the theory section (See "the theory section" variation from the PGN), } ( 15. O-O { is only move for White. I propose } 15... Qb4 $1 { with good play. } ) 15... Nb4 $1 { [%cal Gh7c2] [%csl Gc2] [%csl Gh7] There are problems on c2. Just pause for a minute and worship the Caro-Kann bishop on h7! } 16. Rd4 { In a few games White has tried the forcing } ( 16. a3 Nxc2 17. Rxd5 { , but after the precise } 17... exd5 18. e6 fxe6 19. Nxg7+ Kd7 $1 20. Qf7+ Kc6 { Black was winning in Zezulkin-S. Pedersen, Denmark 1992. } ) 16... Nxc2 17. Ra4 Qc5 { Black is winning. } 18. Rd1 b5 19. a3 { An imaginative defence. The rook can't be taken. } 19... Qc6 $1 { But this wins material. } 20. Rad4 Nxd4 21. Rxd4 Bg6 { With complete control for Black. } 22. Qf3 { Or } ( 22. Ng3 Bxa3 { . } ) 22... Rc8 23. Kd2 a5 { [%cal Gb5b4] Opening lines. } 24. Ke1 b4 25. axb4 axb4 26. Ne2 Qc2 { Black's queen gets into White's camp and quickly spells the end. In time trouble come a few nice tactical shots, but of course the game is decided. } 27. Nhf4 Bc5 28. Qg3 Qxb2 29. Rd1 Qa3 30. Nd3 Be7 31. Bc1 Bxh4 $1 { [%csl Ga3] [%csl Gg3] } 32. Qe3 { Or } ( 32. Bxa3 Bxg3 33. Bxb4 Rh1+ 34. Kd2 Rxd1+ 35. Kxd1 Bxd3 36. Nxg3 Rc4 { . } ) 32... Qa5 33. Bd2 Bg5 $1 { [%cal Gh8h1] } 34. f4 ( 34. Qxg5 Rh1+ { . } ) 34... Rh1+ 35. Ng1 Bh4+ 36. Kf1 Qb5 { [%cal Gb5f1] } 0-1 

